sher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] | date = 30 May 2012 | title = Perry looking for new W-League club| accessdate = 13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Individual====\n* [[Canberra United FC|Canberra United]] Player of the Year: [[2009 Canberra United W-League season|2009]]<ref name=sweeps/>\n* [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] Young Player of the Year: [[2009 W-League (Australia)|2009]]<ref name=\"young\"/>\n\n==Books==\n===Non-fiction===\n*''Perspective'' (Sydney: HarperCollins, 2019; {{ISBN|9781460758083}})\n===Children's books===\n*''Pocket Rocket'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 1 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2016; {{ISBN|9780143781240}})\n*''Magic Feet'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 2 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2016; {{ISBN|9780143781264}})\n*''Winning Touch'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 3 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2017; {{ISBN|9780143781288}})\n*''Double Time'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 4 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2017; {{ISBN|9780143781301}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{FIFA player|326966}}\n*[http://www.cricket.com.au/players/ellyse-perry/1aMxKNyEOUiJqhq7N5Tlwg Ellyse Perry] at [[Cricket Australia]]\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=275487}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Biography|Cricket|New South Wales|Sports}}\n{{Navboxes\n | title = Links to Ellyse Perry-related articles\n | titlestyle = background: gold; color: green\n | list =\n{{100 WODI wickets}}\n{{Australian Woman Cricketer of the Year}}\n{{Wisden Leading Woman Cricketer in the World}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Australia Squads (Cricket)\n|bg = #FFD700\n|fg = #008000\n|list1 =\n{{Australia Squad 2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Australia Squad 2010 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2012 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2014 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2016 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2017 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Australia Squad 2018 ICC Women's World Twenty20}}\n{{Sydney Sixers 2017\u20132018 WBBL Champions}}\n{{Loughborough Lightning (cricket)}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Australia Squads (Soccer)\n|bg = #FFE605\n|fg = #005800\n|list1 =\n{{Australia squad 2008 AFC Women's Asian Cup}}\n{{Australia Squad 2011 Women's World Cup}}\n}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Ellyse}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:2011 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Australian women cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia women Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia women One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia women Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australian women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australia women's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Central Coast Mariners FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:Canberra United FC players]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Loughborough Lightning (WCSL) cricketers]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Breakers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Sydney Sixers (WBBL) cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sydney FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:W-League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football defenders]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pymble Ladies' College]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too long}}\n{{short description|Australian sportswoman}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Ellyse Perry\n| female = true\n| image = 2017\u201318 W Ashes A v E Test 17-11-10 Perry portrait (02).jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Perry during the Women's Ashes Test in 2017\n| country = Australia\n| fullname = Ellyse Alexandra Perry\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|11|3|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Wahroonga, New South Wales]], Australia\n| heightcm = 176\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast]]\n| role = [[All-rounder]]\n| international = true\n| testdebutdate = 15 February\n| testdebutyear = 2008\n| testdebutagainst = England\n| testcap = 152\n| lasttestdate = 18 July\n| lasttestyear = 2019\n| lasttestagainst = England\n| odidebutdate = 22 July\n| odidebutyear = 2007\n| odidebutagainst = New Zealand\n| odicap = 109\n| lastodidate = 9 October\n| lastodiyear = 2019\n| lastodiagainst = Sri Lanka\n| odishirt = 8\n| T20Idebutdate = 1 February\n| T20Idebutyear = 2008\n| T20Idebutagainst = England\n| T20Icap = 21\n|        lastT20Idate = 2 March\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2020\n|     lastT20Iagainst = New Zealand\n| T20Ishirt = 8\n\n| club1 = [[Victoria_women's_cricket_team|Victoria]]\n| year1 = 2020\u2013\n| club2 = [[New South Wales Breakers]]\n| year2 = 2007\u20132019\n| club3 = [[Sydney Sixers (WBBL)|Sydney Sixers]]\n| year3 = 2015\u2013\n| club4 = [[Loughborough Lightning (WCSL)|Loughborough Lightning]]\n| year4 = {{nowrap|2016\u20132017}}\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Women's Test cricket|WTest]]\n| matches1 = 8\n| runs1 = 624\n| bat avg1 = 78.00\n| 100s/50s1 = 2/2\n| top score1 = 213[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries1 = 1,534\n| wickets1 = 31\n| bowl avg1 = 18.19\n| fivefor1 = 2\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 6/32\n| catches/stumpings1 = 5/\u2013\n| column2 = [[Women's One Day International|WODI]]\n| matches2 = 112\n| runs2 = 3,022\n| bat avg2 = 52.10\n| 100s/50s2 = 2/27\n| top score2 = 112[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries2 = 5,110\n| wickets2 = 152\n| bowl avg2 = 24.29\n| fivefor2 = 3\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 7/22\n| catches/stumpings2 = 37/\u2013\n| column3 = [[Women's Twenty20 International|WT20I]]\n| matches3 = 118\n| runs3 = 1,197\n| bat avg3 = 28.50\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/4\n| top score3 = 60[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 2,231\n| wickets3 = 114\n| bowl avg3 = 19.14\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 4/12\n| catches/stumpings3 = 36/\u2013\n| column4 = [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]]\n| matches4 = 70\n| runs4 = 2,612\n| bat avg4 = 53.30\n| 100s/50s4 = 2/17\n| top score4 = 103[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries4 = 1201\n| wickets4 = 32\n| bowl avg4 = 37.53\n| fivefor4 = 0\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 2/11\n| catches/stumpings4 = 25/\u2013\n| date = 2 March\n| year = 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ausvengwomen/content/player/275487.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Ellyse Alexandra Perry''' (born 3 November 1990) is an Australian sportswoman who made her debut for both the [[Australia women's national cricket team|Australian cricket]] and the [[Australia women's national soccer team]] at the age of 16. She played her first cricket international in July 2007 before earning her first football cap for [[Australia]] a month later. Perry is the youngest person to represent Australia in cricket and the first Australian to have appeared in both cricket and football World Cups.<ref name=Darlings>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/darlings-of-the-nation-as-matildas-join-the-elite-20110707-1h4u2.html|title=Darlings of the nation as Matildas join the elite|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> She has gone on to widely be considered one of the greatest female cricketers ever. \n\nPerry was fast-tracked to make her [[Women's One Day International cricket|Women's One Day International]] (WODI) debut for Australia against [[New Zealand national women's cricket team|New Zealand]], three months before playing a single match for her state [[New South Wales Breakers|New South Wales]] in the [[Women's National Cricket League]] (WNCL). In 2007\u201308, she made her debut for [[New South Wales]] and won the WNCL with them, and at the end of the season, she made her [[Women's Test cricket]] debut in [[Bowral]] against [[England women's cricket team|England]]. During the season, she was the player of the match in her [[Women's Twenty20 International]] (WT20I) debut against England, and made her maiden WODI half-century against [[New Zealand]].\n\nPerry took 4 [[wicket]]s for 23 [[run (cricket)|runs]] in the final of the 2008\u201309 WNCL to help New South Wales defend their title. She then took nine wickets as Australia came fourth in the [[2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|2009 World Cup]] held in Australia. She was ineffective during the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20]] in England, taking only two wickets in Australia's four matches.\n\nIn 2009\u201310, Perry took 22 wickets and scored 148 runs as New South Wales won the WNCL again. She then took 18 wickets in 10 WODIs against New Zealand at the end of the season, as the Australians won all the matches. During these matches, Perry took her maiden five-wicket WODI haul. Perry played in each of Australia's matches at the [[2010 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2010 World Twenty20]] in the West Indies, taking 3 wickets for 18 runs and being named player of the match in the final as Australia defeated New Zealand by three runs to claim the title. In December 2017, she won the inaugural ICC Women's Cricketer of the Year award.<ref name=\"ICCW\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21834245/ellyse-perry-declared-icc-women-cricketer-year |title=Ellyse Perry declared ICC's Women's Cricketer of the Year |accessdate=21 December 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, during the [[2018 ICC Women's World Twenty20]] tournament in the West Indies, Perry became the first cricketer for Australia, male or female, to play in 100 Twenty20 International matches.<ref name=\"100T20I\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/ellyse-perry-first-australian-to-reach-t20-milestone-20181117-p50gng.html |title=Ellyse Perry first Australian to reach cricketing milestone |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref> In the final of the same tournament, she became the first cricketer for Australia, male or female, to take 100 wickets in Twenty20 International matches.<ref name=\"100WicketsWT20I\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/match-report/australia-england-world-t20-final-highlights-healy-perry-lanning-knight-shurbsole-wyatt/2018-11-25 |title=Australia win fourth World T20 trophy |work=Cricket Australia |accessdate=25  November 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, during the [[Australia women's cricket team in England in 2019|Women's Ashes]], Perry became the first player, male or female, to score 1,000 runs and take 100 wickets in Twenty20 International cricket.<ref name=\"first100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/match-report/australia-england-second-t20-live-scores-video-highlights-report-meg-lanning-ellyse-perry/2019-07-29 |title=Australia maintain unbeaten Ashes run |work=Cricket Australia |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nA [[Defender (association football)|defender]], Perry represented Australia at the [[2008 AFC Women's Asian Cup|2008 Asian Cup]], and scored in the match against South Korea. She played for the [[Central Coast Mariners W-League|Central Coast Mariners]] in the Australian [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] during the [[W-League 2008-09|2008\u201309]] season, before transferring to [[Canberra United]] the following year. In June 2010, Perry began her media career by hosting the football-related show ''Football Stars of Tomorrow'', screened on the digital sports channel [[10 Bold|One HD]]. However she hasn't played football for the national team since as the team did not call her up again.\n\n==Personal==\nPerry was born in the [[Sydney]] suburb of [[Wahroonga, New South Wales|Wahroonga]] and attended Beecroft Public School,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dapin |first1=Mark |title=Ellyse Perry: Australian sport's pitch-perfect poster girl |url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/ellyse-perry-australian-sports-pitchperfect-poster-girl-20151130-glb6wc.html |accessdate=16 July 2018 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=10 December 2015}}</ref> and [[Pymble Ladies' College]], completing year 12 in 2008. At Pymble, she was Sports Captain, Athletics Captain and Cricket Captain.<ref name=\"cricinfo\">{{cricinfo|ref=ausvengwomen/content/player/275487.html}}, retrieved 20 March 2008.</ref><ref name=\"telegraph\">''[http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23210141-5001023,00.html Teen prodigy must decide between soccer and cricket]'' from ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'', 14 February 2008, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref> During her time at school she played a range of sports beside cricket and soccer such as tennis, athletics, touch football and golf. She is currently studying Economic and Social Sciences at the [[University of Sydney]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wasley|first=Alice|title=Levelling the Playing Field|newspaper=Sunday Herald Sun Magazine|date=22 January 2012|page=17}}</ref> Perry is a regular on the [[Triple J]] radio breakfast show with [[Tom Ballard]] and Alex Dyson to present her segment \u2019Perry Good Sports Woman\u2019.\n\nIn 2013, Perry was ranked by ''[[SportsPro]]'' magazine as the 36th most marketable sportsperson in the world, and the most marketable Australian athlete.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ellyse Perry the most marketable Australian athlete|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/neymar-is-the-worlds-most-marketable-sportsman-ellyse-perry-the-most-marketable-australian-athlete/story-e6frf423-1226642070622#.UfZUhqwcv80|work=foxsports.com.au|accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=All-round Ellyse very, Perry good|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/allround-ellyse-very-perry-good-20140127-31iwu.html|accessdate=28 January 2014 | location=Melbourne|work=The Age}}</ref> She also appeared in a commercial shoot for [[Jockey International|Jockey]] underwear.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|title=Perry steps out of clothes, and comfort zone|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/perry-steps-out-of-clothes-and-comfort-zone-20130727-2qru5.html|accessdate=29 July 2013|newspaper=canberratimes.com.a|date=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729153559/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/perry-steps-out-of-clothes-and-comfort-zone-20130727-2qru5.html|archive-date=29 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 October 2013, Perry went public with her relationship with Australian rugby player [[Matt Toomua]] in their appearance at the [[John Eales Medal]] ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/ellyse-perry-takes-time-out-from-busy-cricket-and-soccer-schedule-to-hook-up-with-wallaby-matt-toomua/story-fni0cvc9-1226747402057|title=\nEllyse Perry takes time out from busy cricket and soccer schedule to hook up with Wallaby Matt Toomua|accessdate=26 October 2013|newspaper=dailytelegraph.com.au|date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/ellyse-perry-and-matt-toomua-go-public-with-their-relationship/story-fni2flhh-1226689739030|title=\nEllyse Perry and matt toomua go public with their relationship|accessdate=26 October 2013|newspaper=dailytelegraph.com.au|date=1 August 2013}}</ref> Less than a year later on 20 August 2014 Perry and Toomua announced their engagement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-union/union-news/matt-toomua-ellyse-perry--and-nic-white-20140821-106rgv.html|title=Matt Toomua, Ellyse Perry ... and Nic White|accessdate=21 August 2014|newspaper=smh.com.au|date=21 August 2014}}</ref> They married on 19 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-union/union-news/dual-international-ellyse-perry-and-matt-toomua-get-married-20151222-gltfj5.html|title=Ellyse Perry hits winning runs for Sydney Sixers .. then marries Matt Toomua|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Perry wrote a series of books with Sheryl Clark. These four books follow a young sport crazy Ellyse transitioning from Primary School to High School with her two friends Charlie and Jazz.\n\n==Cricket==\nIn [[cricket]], Perry is an [[all-rounder]] who [[batting (cricket)|bats]] right-handed and [[bowling (cricket)|bowls]] with a right-handed [[fast bowling|fast-medium]] action.<ref name=\"cricinfo\" /><ref name=\"cricketaus\">[http://www.cricket.com.au/default.aspx?s=playerswomendetails&profileid=299 Perry, Ellyse] from [[Cricket Australia]], retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref>\n\nPerry had a rapid rise into the Australian team. Soon after turning 16, she played for [[New South Wales]] in the Under-19 interstate tournament in January 2007. In three matches she scored 74 runs at an [[Batting average (cricket)|average]] of 37.00 and took three wickets with an [[Economy rate (cricket)|economy rate]] of 13.66 as her state won all three matches.<ref name=o/> A month later, in February 2007, she was selected for the [[Australia]] Youth for a tour of [[New Zealand]] in February 2007, where they played New Zealand A, the hosts' second-string team. She was not overly successful and scored 43 runs at 21.50 and took only one wicket\u2014that of [[Victoria Lind]]\u2014at 100.00 at an economy rate of 4.54.<ref name=o/><ref name=ow/> The three-match series was drawn 1\u20131 after the second match was tied.<ref name=o/>\n\nPerry was then fast-tracked into the senior Australian team for their next series in July 2007, despite having never played a match at senior (non-youth) level.<ref name=\"cricketaus\" /><ref name=o/><ref name=\"cricketarchive\">[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/187/187173/187173.html Ellyse Perry] from CricketArchive, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref> In the second match of the series, she made her [[One-Day International]] debut against [[New Zealand national women's cricket team|New Zealand]] in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] on 22 July 2007 at the age of 16 years and 8 months: this made her the youngest ever cricketer to represent Australia, male or female.<ref name=\"cricinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbcODIdebut\">''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/womens_cricket/6910534.stm Mason spoils schoolgirl's debut]'' from [[BBC Sport]], 22 July 2007, retrieved 17 February 2008.</ref> In her first match, she took 2 wickets for 37 runs from eight [[over (cricket)|overs]] as the visitors made 209.<ref name=o/> Her first wicket was [[Maria Fahey]], whom she [[bowled]] for 11. She later had [[Sara McGlashan]] caught by [[Emma Sampson]] for 28.<ref name=ow>{{Cite web| title=Player Oracle EA Perry|url=https://cricketarchive.com/cgi-bin/player_oracle_reveals_results2.cgi?playernumber=187173&testing=0&opponentmatch=exact&playername=IK%20Pathan&resulttype=All&matchtype=All&teammatch=exact&startwicket=&homeawaytype=All&opponent=&endwicket=&wicketkeeper=&searchtype=WicketsTakenList&endscore=&playermatch=contains&branding=cricketarchive&captain=&endseason=&startscore=&team=&startseason= |accessdate=14 May 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref> Coming in at No. 9, she then made 19 from 20 balls as Australia were dismissed for 174 to lose by 35 runs.<ref name=o/><ref name=odi/> Perry took a wicket in the third and fourth matches and ended her debut series with 27 runs at 9.00 and four wickets at 30.50.<ref name=o/> Australia won the third and fourth matches to take a series-winning 3\u20131 lead before losing the final game.<ref name=auslistw>{{Cite web | url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/team/238.html?class=9;template=results;type=team;view=results | title=Statsguru \u2013 Australia Women \u2013 Women's One-Day Internationals \u2013 Team analysis | publisher=[[Cricinfo]] | accessdate=14 April 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121205003839/http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/team/238.html?class=9;template=results;type=team;view=results | archivedate=5 December 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===WNCL debut===\n[[File:2017\u201318 WNCL NSWB v ACTM 17-11-26 Perry (04).jpg|thumb|Perry on her way to 127* for the [[NSW Breakers]] against the ACT Meteors in 2017]]\nDuring the 2007\u201308 Australian summer, Perry made her debut for [[New South Wales Breakers|New South Wales]] in the [[Women's National Cricket League]] (WNCL) in the first match of the season against [[South Australian Scorpions|South Australia]], taking 2/29 from ten overs and taking a catch in a seven-wicket win. Her first wicket in her WNCL career was that of leading batsman [[Karen Rolton]], rated the best in the world at the time, caught by [[Lisa Sthalekar]].<ref name=o/><ref name=ow/> In the second match of the double-header, she batted for the first time, scoring 12 and then claiming 3/21 in a 25-run win.<ref name=o/> She then went wicketless in two victories over Victoria. In the fifth match of the season against Queensland, she scored 37 in New South Wales' 189 and took 2/10 with the ball to help seal a 66-run win.<ref name=o/> In the penultimate match, she took 0/51 from ten overs against Western Australia and was omitted from the next day's match. Perry ended her first season for New South Wales with 66 runs at 13.20 and nine wickets at 24.00 from seven matches.<ref name=o/> The final against South Australia was washed out by rain without a ball being bowled and New South Wales were awarded the WNCL title on account of ranking first in the round-robin phase. In two [[Twenty20]] matches for her state, Perry took a total of 1/34 from six overs and did not bat as New South Wales won both matches.<ref name=o/>\n\nPerry was retained for Australia's international engagements at the end of the season, a home series against [[England women's cricket team|England]] and a tour to [[New Zealand]].<ref name=o>{{Cite web| title=Player Oracle EA Perry |url=https://cricketarchive.com/cgi-bin/player_oracle_reveals_results2.cgi?playernumber=187173&opponentmatch=exact&playername=Meckiff&resulttype=All&matchtype=All&teammatch=exact&startwicket=&homeawaytype=All&opponent=&endwicket=&wicketkeeper=&searchtype=InningsList&endscore=&playermatch=contains&branding=cricketarchive&captain=&endseason=&startscore=&team=&startseason= |accessdate=14 May 2009 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=auslistw/>\n\nThe series against England started with a WT20I in front of a large crowd at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] (MCG) as the curtain-raiser for a WT20I game between the [[Australia national cricket team|Australian]] and [[India national cricket team|Indian men]]. Perry came in late in Australia's innings and struck 29 [[not out]] off 25 balls to help them reach 5/127. She then took 4/20 off her 4 [[over (cricket)|overs]] of bowling, and effected a crucial [[run out]] as the tourists were restricted to 8/106 and a 21-run defeat.<ref name=\"scorecardTwenty20debut\">[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ausvengwomen/engine/match/312444.html Australia Women v England Women, 1 February 2008, scorecard] from [[Cricinfo]], retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref><ref name=\"bbcTwenty20debut\">''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/womens_cricket/7221628.stm Perry too much for England women]'' from [[BBC Sport]], 1 February 2008, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref><ref name=\"cricinfoTwenty20debut\">''[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ausvengwomen/content/story/334492.html Move over, Watson. Introducing Ellyse Perry]'' from [[Cricinfo]], 1 February 2008, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref> In the first WODI, held at the MCG, Perry was attacked by the English batsmen, taking 1/51 from eight overs. Elevated up the batting order to No. 7,<ref name=odi/> She made 40 from 65 balls without hitting a boundary, her highest score to that point.<ref name=o/><ref name=odi>{{Cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/275487.html?class=9;template=results;type=batting;view=innings |title=Statistics / Statsguru / EA Perry / Women's One-Day Internationals |accessdate=13 November 2017 |publisher=[[Cricinfo]] }}</ref> She was run out as Australia lost by 56 runs.<ref name=o/> She returned to form with ball in the three remaining WODIs, taking 3/24, 2/24 and 3/30 all from eight overs, but managed only 2 and 5 in her remaining innings.<ref name=o/><ref name=odi/> Perry ended the series, which was drawn 2\u20132, with 47 runs at 15.66 and nine wickets at 14.21.<ref name=o/>\n\n===Test debut===\n[[File:2017\u201318 W Ashes A v E Test 17-11-09 Perry portrait (01).jpg|thumb|left|Perry during [[English women's cricket team in Australia in 2017\u201318|2017\u201318 Women's Ashes Test]] at [[North Sydney Oval]]'']]\nThe series ended with a one-off Test, starting in [[Bowral]] on 15 February 2008, when at the age of 17 years and 3 months, Perry became the youngest ever Australian Test cricketer.<ref name=\"cricinfo\" /><ref name=\"smh\">''[http://www.smh.com.au/news/cricket/ellyse-wants-to-make-england-history/2008/02/14/1202760494918.html Ellyse wants to make England history]'' from ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 15 February 2008, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref> The hosts batted first and collapsed to be 5/59 after 31.1 overs on the first day, bringing Perry to the crease to join [[Kate Blackwell]]. Perry made 21 from 77 balls in 79 minutes, hitting two fours, before being [[run out]] by a throw from [[Laura Marsh]] to English wicket-keeper [[Sarah Taylor (cricketer)|Sarah Taylor]]. This ended a 50-run partnership, the largest of the innings; Australia were eventually out for 154 on the first day.<ref name=t2008/> Perry then opened the bowling, taking the new ball alongside [[Emma Sampson]]. The pair failed to take a wicket in their initial spell and England reached stumps without loss. The next day, Perry had opener [[Caroline Atkins]] caught by wicket-keeper [[Leonie Coleman]] for 15 to claim her maiden Test wicket to leave England at 1/26 after 22.4 overs. After Sampson removed [[Beth Morgan (cricketer)|Beth Morgan]] the next over without addition to the score, England captain [[Charlotte Edwards]] combined with [[Claire Taylor]] to put on a partnership of 159 before Perry removed top-scorer Edwards for 94, also caught by Coleman.<ref name=ow/><ref name=t2008/> This wicket sparked a collapse as England lost their remaining eight wickets for 59 runs. Perry also took her first catch in Tests; she caught [[Rosalie Birch]] to give fellow debutant [[Kirsten Pike]] her first Test wicket.<ref name=t2008/> Perry ended with 2/49 from 23 overs as the tourists replied with 244 to take a 90-run lead.<ref name=o/>\n\nShe then came in at 5/198 in the second innings and struggled, making only six runs from 36 balls in 52 minutes as wickets fell steadily; Australia declared after the fall of their ninth wicket at 9/231, leaving England 142 for victory.<ref name=t2008/> Perry took 1/17 from 13 overs, removing Atkins again, this time [[leg before wicket]] as the visitors took a six-wicket win to sour her Test debut.<ref name=o/><ref name=t2008>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/129/129766.html |title=Australia Women v England Women |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nAustralia then crossed the [[Tasman Sea|Tasman]] for the Rose Bowl series held at the [[Bert Sutcliffe Oval]] in [[Lincoln, New Zealand|Lincoln]]. After taking 1/21 from eight overs in Australia's 63-run win in the first match, Perry made 28 and 51 in the next two matches; the visitors collapsed to be all out for 156 and 170 respectively and cede a 2\u20131 series deficit. In the fourth match, Perry took 2/51 from 9.4 overs, taking the last wicket to seal a six-run win and level the series. In the deciding match, Perry was attacked by the hosts' batsmen and conceded 38 runs from five overs, but the Australians reached their target with eight wickets to spare and to claim the series. Perry ended with 80 runs at 26.66 and four wickets at 41.00, but she was uneconomical, conceding 4.70 runs per over.<ref name=o/>\n\nAt the start of the 2008\u201309 season, Australia hosted an WODI series against India in Sydney. Perry played in four of the matches, missing the third fixture. She took 3/21 from nine overs in the fourth WODI, her best WODI figures at the time, helping to seal a 118-run win. She ended the series with 16 runs at 16.00 and six wickets at 19.33 and an economy rate of 3.41.<ref name=o/> During the season's WNCL, Perry scored 24 runs at 8.00 and took 12 wickets at 24.25. Perry was low key in the early part of the season, taking only five wickets in the first six matches. After taking 2/32 and 1/37 against [[Victorian Spirit|Victoria]] in the last two round-robin matches, both of which ended in victories, Perry peaked in the final, where New South Wales met the Victorians again. She took 4/23 to help bowl out the Victorians for 117. Perry then came to the crease as her state was on the verge of victory, and was unbeaten without scoring when the winning runs were brought up with six wickets in hand.<ref name=o/> In two [[Twenty20]] matches for New South Wales, she took four wickets at 7.75 at an economy rate of 4.42, and scored 25 runs at 12.50. New South Wales won one match and lost the other.<ref name=o/>\n\nAfter the WNCL finished, the Australians toured New Zealand for the Rose Bowl series, and Perry again struggled with the ball as she did in her previous visit to the country. Perry played in the first three matches and took one wicket at 77.00 and at an economy rate of 4.05. She made 29 in the first WODI and ended with 40 runs at 20.00.<ref name=o/> The Australians then returned home for the [[2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|Women's World Cup]], held in New South Wales. In her only warm-up match, she was attacked by England's batsmen, taking 1/42 from seven overs.<ref name=o/>\n\n===2009 World Cup and World Twenty20===\n[[File:Rolton & Perry.jpg|thumb|Perry and [[Karen Rolton|Rolton]] at the [[2009 Women's Cricket World Cup]]'']]\nIn the opening match of the World Cup campaign, held at [[North Sydney Oval]], Perry was attacked by the New Zealand batsmen, but also took wickets, ending with 3/40 from six overs. She made 17 not out as Australia fell short of their target on the [[Duckworth-Lewis method]].<ref name=o/> Australia then needed to win their two remaining group matches to reach the Super Six phase. Perry took 0/28 from five overs and did not bat as Australia defeated [[south Africa national women's cricket team|South Africa]] by 61 runs. She then scored 36 and took 2/28 from ten overs in a 47-run win over the [[West Indies women's cricket team|West Indies]].<ref name=o/> In the first Super Six match, the Indians attacked her bowling and she conceded 56 runs from nine wicketless overs. She then made a [[Duck (cricket)|duck]] as Australia made 7/218, falling 17 runs short of their target.<ref name=o/> Perry then scored 12 not out and took 2/16 from seven overs as Australia defeated [[Pakistan national women's cricket team|Pakistan]] by 107 runs. She missed Australia's final Super Six match against England, and although the hosts won, it was not enough for them to place in the top two in the standings and qualify for the final. In the third-place playoff, she made 2 of Australia's 142, and then took 2/26 from 6.5 overs, but was not able to prevent a three-wicket defeat.<ref name=o/> Perry ended the tournament with 67 runs at 22.33 and took nine wickets at 21.55 at an economy rate of 4.42.<ref name=o/>\n\nPerry was selected for Australia's team for the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20|inaugural Women's World Twenty20]] held in England in 2009. The Australians hosted New Zealand for a three-match series in tropical [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] at the beginning of June before the World Cup, and Perry played in the first two matches, taking 1/33 and 1/9 from her four overs.<ref name=o/> Arriving in the northern hemisphere she took 3/16 from three overs in the team's only warm-up on English soil, a five-run win against the hosts.\n\nHowever, Perry was not successful in the tournament. After making four not out in Australia's 8/123, she was attacked by the New Zealand batsmen and ended with 0/31 from three overs in a nine-wicket win. She then took 0/6 in two overs against the West Indies, and 1/13 in two overs against South Africa. She was not required to bat in either match as Australia won both to reach the semi-finals against the hosts.<ref name=o/> She did not bat and took 1/32 from four overs as England overhauled Australia's score of 5/163 to reach the final, which they won. Perry ended the tournament with two wickets at 41.00 at an economy rate of 7.36.<ref name=o/>\n\nPerry and the Australians stayed in England for a bilateral series against the hosts, who were the reigning world champions in both WODIs and WT20Is, after the end of the World Twenty20. She played in all five WODIs, and was not successful, taking only three wickets at 50.00 and an economy rate of 5.55.<ref name=o/> Her best performance was in the third match at [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], scoring 16 not out before taking 2/31 from six overs in a two-wicket defeat. She ended the series with 34 runs at 17.00.<ref name=o/>\n\nEngland won all the WODI matches except the last, which was washed out.<ref name=o/> Perry played in the one-off Test match at [[New Road, Worcester|New Road]] in Worcestershire. Coming in with the score on 6/257, Perry scored 18 not out from 63 balls as wickets fell steadily at the other end and Australia were bowled out for 309. She then took 1/49 from 14 overs, bowling England captain and leading batsman Edwards for 10, to help Australia take a 41-run lead. She then made 6 before being dismissed by spinner [[Holly Colvin]] as Australia set the hosts a target of 273 before the match was drawn.<ref name=o/> She took 1/14 from eight overs in the second innings,<ref name=o/> removing opener [[Lydia Greenway]] caught and bowled as the hosts ended on 3/106.<ref name=t2009>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/204/204506.html |title=England Women v Australia Women |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nPerry started the 2009\u201310 WNCL strongly, scoring 66 in New South Wales' 198, her highest score in limited-overs cricket, before taking 3/42 from ten overs in a 15-run win over Queensland. She followed this with 2/19 in the second match of the double-header and 3/30 in the next game against the [[ACT Meteors]]. She took four wickets in the next three matches before peaking in the final double-header of the season, against South Australia. In the first match, she took a career-best figure of 5/19 from eight overs to help dismiss South Australia for only 45. She then made an unbeaten 17 in the top-order to seal an eight-wicket win. The next day, she made 30 and then took 4/28 from 10 overs to ensure a 76-run win.<ref name=o/> In the final against Victoria, Perry scored 17 before being run out as New South Wales made 9/206. She then took 1/11 from her six overs to help dismiss the Victorians for 147 and seal a fifth consecutive WNCL title for New South Wales.<ref name=o/> Perry ended the season with 148 runs at 29.60 and 22 wickets at 10.63 at an economy rate of 3.29 from nine matches.<ref name=o/>\n\nIn contrast, Perry had an unsuccessful time in domestic Twenty20 cricket, now part of a full interstate tournament, scoring five runs at 1.66 and taking three wickets at 39.33 at an economy rate of 5.61 in seven matches.<ref name=o/> Perry's best bowling came in the match against Tasmania, taking 2/14 from four overs. New South Wales met Victoria in the final, where Perry was attacked and conceded 17 runs from her two overs as Victoria made 5/127. Perry then made her only runs of the tournament, scoring five as New South Wales were bowled out for 75, handing Victoria a 51-run win and the title.<ref name=o/>\n\nPerry then played in the Rose Bowl series against New Zealand, starting with a five-match home WODI series. In each of the first two matches, held at the [[Adelaide Oval]] and won by the hosts, she took two wickets, and she also took two catches in the first match.<ref name=o/>\n\nThe last three matches of the series were held at the [[Junction Oval]] in Melbourne. In the third WODI, she scored an unbeaten 22 from 15 balls in the [[Glossary of cricket terms#D|death overs]], and took 1/33 in a 102-run win that sealed the series.<ref name=o/><ref name=odi/> In the fourth match of the series, she took 5/31, her best bowling figures in an WODI, helping to bowl out the tourists for 162, setting up a ten-wicket win.<ref name=o/> In the final match, she scored 30 from 22 balls in the closing overs,<ref name=odi/> and then took 3/33 to seal a 103-run win and a 5\u20130 [[Whitewash (sport)|whitewash]]. She had taken 63 runs at 31.50 and taken 13 wickets at 12.61 with an economy rate of 4.29.<ref name=o/>\n\nThe WODIs were followed by three WT20Is at [[Bellerive Oval]] in [[Hobart]] and two more in New Zealand at the start of the second phase of the bilateral contests. Perry played in every match and Australia was whitewashed, although she remained effective. She bowled her quota of four overs in each of the matches, and took seven wickets at 12.71 and an economy rate of only 4.45.<ref name=o/> She made 21 runs at 10.50, and took a back-pedalling catch.\n\nAustralia then swept New Zealand 3\u20130 in the WODIs in New Zealand. In the first match, she took 2/44 in the hosts' 6/228 and then made 27 from 30 balls in the [[Glossary of cricket terms#R|run chase]] as the tourists struggled. Although she fell late, the Australians scraped home from the last ball of the match.<ref name=auslistw/> Perry took 2/49 and 1/25 in the next two matches and was not required to bat as the Australians chased their target in both matches with six wickets in hand. She ended the series with five wickets at 23.60 at 4.37.<ref name=o/>\n\n===2010 World Twenty20 triumph===\n[[File:Ellyse Perry batting.jpg|thumb|left|Perry preparing to play a shot.]]\nPerry was part of the [[2010 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2010 World Twenty20]] winning team in the [[West Indies]] and played in all of Australia's matches. She was the player of the match in the final.<ref name=nz1>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/290/290068.html |title=Australia Women v New Zealand Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=pak>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/290/290073.html |title=Australia Women v Pakistan Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=eng>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/250/250770.html |title=Australia Women v England Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=rsa>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/250/250773.html |title=Australia Women v South Africa Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=wi>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/250/250778.html |title=West Indies Women v Australia Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=ind>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/250/250781.html |title=Australia Women v India Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref name=nz2>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/250/250783.html |title=Australia Women v New Zealand Women |accessdate=4 June 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref> In the first warm-up match against New Zealand, which Australia lost by 18 runs, Perry took 1/22 from three overs, removing Elizabeth Perry for 10. She then made 2 not out from 2 balls at the end of Australia's innings.<ref name=nz1/> In the last warm-up match against Pakistan, Perry was not required to bat as Australia made 5/166. She ran out Pakistani captain [[Sana Mir]] and bowled [[Nida Dar]] and [[Batool Fatima]] to end with 2/13 from 3.3 overs as Australia won by 82 runs.<ref name=pak/>\n\nAustralia were grouped with defending champions [[England women's cricket team|England]], [[South Africa national women's cricket team|South Africa]] and the [[West Indies women's cricket team|West Indies]].<ref name=eng/><ref name=rsa/><ref name=wi/> In the first match, Perry caught [[Jenny Gunn]] from the bowling of Sthalekar and then bowled [[Katherine Brunt]] as England collapsed late in their innings, losing 6/22, leaving 15 balls unused. During Australia's pursuit of 105 for victory, Perry came in at 5/60 in the 12th over and made 1 from 3 balls before Gunn ran her out, leaving Australia at 6/62 in the 14th over. This was part of a passage of play during which Australia lost 3/18 in 29 balls, and at 7/63, they needed 42 runs from 34 for victory with three wickets in hand. Eventually, Australia recovered, before [[Rene Farrell]] was [[run out]] going for the winning run from the third last ball available, leaving the scores tied.<ref name=eng/>\n\nA [[Super Over]] eventuated, and both teams made 2/6, suffering run outs in an attempt to secure a seventh run on the final ball. Australia was awarded the match because they had hit more [[six (cricket)|sixes]] in the match\u2014[[Jess Cameron]] scored the solitary six.<ref name=eng/>\n\nIn the next match against South Africa, Perry made five runs from ten balls before being caught, the last player dismissed as Australia ended on 155 with three balls unused. This was part of a collapse in the death overs as Australia lost their last six wickets for 16, including the last four wickets for four runs. Perry came in to bat after Australia lost both Cameron and [[Sarah Elliott (cricketer)|Sarah Elliott]] with the score on 139, and saw three partners leave before being dismissed herself.<ref name=rsa/> In the run-chase, South Africa reached 0/33 from 5.3 overs before Perry ran out their captain [[Cri-Zelda Brits]]. Perry later bowled [[Chloe Tryon]] late in the innings and ended with 1/16 from three overs as Australia completed a 22-run win.<ref name=rsa/>\n\nPerry was not required to bat as Australia finished on 7/133 in the final group match against the West Indies. In the second over of the run-chase, Perry ran out [[Juliana Nero]] with a throw to [[Rene Farrell]]. She later had [[Deandra Dottin]] caught behind for a duck, before dismissing [[Pamela Lavine]] in the penultimate over. Perry ended with 2/19 from three overs as Australia won by nine runs to finish the group stage unbeaten at the top of their quartet.<ref name=wi/>\n\nAustralia went on to face [[India national women's cricket team|India]] in the semi-final, and Perry took 1/19 from her four overs as India made 5/119. At the start of the 17th over bowled by Perry, India were on 2/88, and the partnership between [[Harmanpreet Kaur]] and [[Poonam Raut]] had yielded 57 runs. Perry ran out Kaur from the first ball of the over, and two balls later, the Indian captain [[Jhulan Goswami]] was run out by Blackwell. Perry then had Raut caught from the next ball and India had lost 3/1 in four balls. Perry was required to neither bat nor bowl as the Indians ended with 3/119, which was chased down by the Australians with seven wickets and seven balls to spare.<ref name=ind/>\n\nAustralia batted first in the final against New Zealand, and Perry was not required as they reached 106, losing their eighth wicket from the last ball of the innings.<ref name=nz2/> New Zealand started their chase solidly, before losing two wickets by the end of the fifth over. Perry's first over was the sixth of the innings, and she dismissed [[Suzie Bates]], who tried to pull but [[Glossary of cricket terms#S|skied]] the ball down the ground and was caught by Elliott, who ran across from mid-off, for 18. In her following over, the eighth of the innings, Perry uprooted [[Amy Satterthwaite]]'s off stump with a ball that kept low and New Zealand were in trouble at 4/29 in the eighth over.<ref name=nz>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wwt202010/engine/current/match/412718.html?innings=2;page=1;view=commentary |title=Australia Women v New Zealand Women \u2013 New Zealand Women innings |accessdate=10 June 2010 |publisher=[[Cricinfo]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520012434/http://www.cricinfo.com/wwt202010/engine/current/match/412718.html?innings=2%3Bpage%3D1%3Bview%3Dcommentary |archivedate=20 May 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPerry was then taken out of the attack and the New Zealanders consolidated and rebuilt the innings.<ref name=nz/> [[Nicola Browne]] and [[Sophie Devine]] put on 41 from as many balls. In the 18th over, Browne was caught behind for 20 from Perry, and New Zealand were 6/103 at the start of the last over, needing 14 runs to win. Perry was given the ball.<ref name=nz/> A single from the first ball put Devine on strike, and she hit four consecutive twos. Devine required five runs from the last ball to win and she struck a powerful straight drive. If the ball had gone past Perry, it could have reached the boundary for a four to tie the match and force a Super Over. Perry stuck out her right foot and the ball deflected to mid-on where Sthalekar stopped the ball and only one run was scored. This sealed an Australian win by three runs. Perry was named the player of the match for her 3/18.<ref name=nz/>\n\n===2013 World Cup triumph===\nPerry was in the Australian team as opening bowler that won the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup|2013 ICC Women's Cricket World Cup]] in Mumbai, India, in which final she had to have a painkilling injection in her ankle to play.<ref name=WC12>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/australian-women-on-top-of-the-world-after-cricket-world-cup-victory-20130218-2eltl.html |title=Australian women on top of the world after cricket World Cup victory | location=Melbourne | work=The Age}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Ashes===\n\nIn June 2015, she was named as one of Australia's touring party for the [[Australian women's cricket team in England and Ireland in 2015|2015 Women's Ashes]] in England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/32964816|date=1 June 2015|accessdate=3 June 2015|title=Women's Ashes: Australia include three potential Test debututants|publisher=BBC}}</ref> She was awarded Player of the Series after making the most runs and taking the most wickets throughout the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/ellyse-perry-player-of-the-womens-ashes-series-jess-jonassen-meg-lanning-megan-schutt/2015-09-01|date=1 September 2015|accessdate=13 November 2017|title=Perry peaks in Ashes triumph|publisher=Cricket Australia}}</ref>\n\n===2018 World Twenty20 and beyond===\nIn October 2018, she was named in Australia's squad for the [[2018 ICC Women's World Twenty20]] tournament in the West Indies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/australia-women-southern-stars-world-t20-squad-bolton-wareham-vlaeminck/2018-10-09 |title=Australia reveal World Twenty20 squad |work=Cricket Australia |accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/876684 |title=Jess Jonassen, Nicole Bolton in Australia's squad for ICC Women's World T20 |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> In the tournament match against [[India women's national cricket team|India]] on 17 November, Perry became the first cricketer for Australia, male or female, to play in 100 Twenty20 International matches.<ref name=\"100T20I\"/> In the final match against [[England women's national cricket team|England]] on 24 November, Perry became the first cricketer for Australia, male or female, to take 100 wickets in Twenty20 International matches.<ref name=\"100WicketsWT20I\"/>\n\nIn April 2019, [[Cricket Australia]] awarded her with a contract ahead of the 2019\u201320 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1179934.html |title=Georgia Wareham handed first full Cricket Australia contract |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1167334 |title=Georgia Wareham included in Australia's 2019-20 contracts list |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Cricket Australia named her in Australia's team for their [[Australia women's cricket team in England in 2019|tour to England]] to contest the [[Women's Ashes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26890086/sophie-molineux-misses-ashes-squad-tayla-vlaeminck-included |title=Molineux misses Ashes squad, Vlaeminck included |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jun/04/tayla-vlaeminck-beats-injury-to-make-australian-womens-ashes-squad |title=Tayla Vlaeminck beats injury to make Australian women's Ashes squad |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> On 7 July 2019, in the third WODI of the Women's Ashes, Perry took the best bowling figures for an Australian in WODIs, with 7 wickets for 22 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jul/07/england-australia-womens-ashes-third-odi-match-report |title=Ellyse Perry takes seven wickets as Australia thrash England in Ashes ODI |work=The Guardian |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> On 19 July 2019, in the first innings  of the Women's Ashes Test match, she set a new record for the most runs scored between dismissals in women's Test cricket with 329 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/19045/report/1168025/day/2/england-women-vs-australia-women-only-test-aus-w-in-england-2019 |title=Rain wrecks England's hopes of Ashes fightback as Perry stars with hundred |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref> She also became the fourth women to hit two consecutive Ashes Test centuries after [[Betty Wilson]], [[Enid Bakewell]] and [[Claire Taylor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1289576 |title=Perry joins distinguished company before rain intervenes |work=International Cricket Council  |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref> In the second WT20I match of the Women's Ashes, Perry became the first player, male or female, to score 1,000 runs and take 100 wickets in Twenty20 International cricket.<ref name=\"first100\"/>\n\nOn 11 September 2019, in the third match [[Australian women's cricket team in the West Indies in 2019\u201320|against the West Indies]], Perry became the third bowler to take [[List of women's One Day International cricket records#Most career wickets|150 wickets in WODI cricket]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://femalecricket.com/women-cricket-news/4983-ellyse-perry-becomes-third-woman-to-claim-150-odi-wickets-after-goswami-and-fitzpatrick.html |title=Ellyse Perry becomes third woman to claim 150 ODI Wickets after Goswami and Fitzpatrick |work=Female Cricket |accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref> In January 2020, she was named in Australia's squad for the [[2020 ICC Women's T20 World Cup]] in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28491572/sophie-molineux-annabel-sutherland-named-australia-t20-world-cup-squad |title=Sophie Molineux and Annabel Sutherland named in Australia's T20 World Cup squad |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic Twenty20 cricket===\n[[File:2018\u201319 WBBL PS v SS 19-01-06 Perry (08).jpg|thumb|Perry bowling for the Sydney Sixers against the Perth Scorchers in 2019]]\nPerry became the first signing and captain of the women [[Sydney Sixers (WBBL)|Sydney Sixers]] in the inaugural season of [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]], and led them to the playoffs and a second-place finish despite losing the first six games in a row. In April 2016, it was announced she would play for [[Loughborough Lightning (WCSL)|Loughborough Lightning]] in the inaugural season of the [[Women's Cricket Super League]] in England.<ref>{{cite news|title=WCSL: Meg Lanning, Suzie Bates and Stafanie Taylor lead overseas signings|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/36043614|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a widely reported incident, a ball Perry hit into the crowd during a WBBL match against the [[Melbourne Stars]] at [[North Sydney Oval]] on 9 December 2017 hit a 13-year-old boy in the face after the ball deflected from a chair. After seeing the ball hit the boy, Perry immediately rushed to the boundary to check on the boy's welfare and direct the on-field medics to his location.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-10/ellyse-perry-shot-hits-child-in-the-face/9244148 Ellyse Perry shot hits boy in the face at Women\u2019s Big Bash as Sydney Sixers go big against Melbourne Stars], ''[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]'', 10 December 2017. Retrieved 10 December 2017.</ref> The boy was transported to hospital by ambulance for observation but was later released. Perry phoned the boy the following morning to check on his wellbeing.<ref>Sewell, Eliza [http://www.news.com.au/sport/cricket/wbbl-boy-hit-in-the-face-by-ellyse-perry-six-at-north-sydney-oval/news-story/e71370b73bccdc45cfe0f8fd19b8ddca WBBL: Boy hit in the face by Ellyse Perry six at North Sydney Oval], ''[[news.com.au]]'', 9 December 2017. Retrieved 10 December 2017.</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, she was named in the [[Sydney Sixers (WBBL)|Sydney Sixers]]' squad for the [[2018\u201319 Women's Big Bash League season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/wbbl-04-all-you-need-to-know-guide-tv-schedule-squads-when-fantasy-best-players/2018-11-30 |title=WBBL04: All you need to know guide |work=Cricket Australia |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/25412608/the-full-squads-wbbl |title=The full squads for the WBBL |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2020 move to Victoria===\nPerry moved to Melbourne in 2019 following her husband's move to play for the Melbourne Rebels. She made her debut for [[Victoria women's cricket team|Victoria]] on 7 January 2020 at the [[Junction Oval]], making 24 runs and taking 1-20 from seven overs after returning from a shoulder injury suffered in the previous WBBL season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Perry back from injury as Vics thrash WA |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/perry-back-from-injury-as-vics-thrash-wa-20200107-p53plx.html |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=Sydney Morning Herald |agency=AAP |date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Football==\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ellyse Perry\n| fullname = Ellyse Alexandra Perry\n| image = Ellyse Perry-Canberra United.jpg\n| image_size = 180\n| caption = Perry playing for [[Canberra United FC|Canberra United]] in 2009\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|11|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Wahroonga, New South Wales|Wahroonga]], [[Australia]]\n| height = {{height|cm=172}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1= 2008\n| youthclubs1= [[NSW Sapphires]]\n| years1 = 2008\u20132009 | years2 =2009\u20132012 | years3 =2012\u20132016\n| clubs1 = [[Central Coast Mariners W-League|Central Coast Mariners]] | clubs2 =[[Canberra United W-League|Canberra United]] | clubs3 =[[Sydney FC W-League|Sydney FC]]\n| caps1 = 3 | goals1 = 0 | caps2 = 24 | goals2 = 2 | caps3 = 20 | goals3 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2007 | nationalyears2 =2007\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Australia women's national under-20 football team|Australia U-20]] | nationalteam2 =[[Australia women's national soccer team|Australia]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | nationalcaps2 = 18 | nationalgoals2 = 3\n| pcupdate = 13 September 2016\n| ntupdate = 17 July 2011\n}}\nIn [[association football|soccer]], Perry plays as a [[defender (football)|defender]].<ref name=\"matildas_asian_cup_squad\">''[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/Women/default.aspx?s=womens_news_feat_news_news_item&id=22293 Matildas hit by loss of key players on eve of Asian Cup] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313084126/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/Women/default.aspx?s=womens_news_feat_news_news_item&id=22293 |date=13 March 2011 }}'' from [[Football Federation Australia]], 25 May 2008, retrieved 24 June 2008.</ref> She played her first match for the Australian national team, an [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Women's qualification|Olympic qualifying match]] against [[Hong Kong women's national football team|Hong Kong]] at the Hong Kong Football Club, on 4 August 2007. She played this match at the age of 16 years and 9 months, and less than two weeks after her international cricket debut. Perry scored a [[goal (sport)|goal]] in the second minute of the match as Australia won 8\u20131.<ref name=\"matildas_debut\">''[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/matildas/default.aspx?s=aus_matildas_news_feat_news_item&id=18717 Youthful Matildas too strong for Hong Kong]'' from [[Football Federation Australia]], 4 August 2007, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref>\n\n{{As of|2008|alt=As of July 2008}}, she has played eleven matches for the national team, including five in the [[2008 AFC Women's Asian Cup]],<ref name=\"ffa_results\">[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/Australia/default.aspx?s=aus_fixtures Fixtures &amp; Results] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521165639/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/Australia/default.aspx?s=aus_fixtures |date=21 May 2008 }} from [[Football Federation Australia]], retrieved 24 June 2008. (Select \"Matildas\" from the Team drop-down selector).</ref><ref name=\"unofficial_matildas\">[http://users2.titanichost.com/australianwomensfootball/profile.asp?player=Ellyse%20Perry&team=Matildas Ellyse Perry Player Profile] from Australian Women's Football unofficial site, retrieved 24 June 2008.</ref> where she scored a goal against [[Korea Republic women's national football team|South Korea]].<ref name=\"matildas_asian_cup_goal\">''[http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/australia/default.aspx?s=aus_news_feat_news_news_item&id=22366 Matildas make it win number two] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527203801/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/australia/default.aspx?s=aus_news_feat_news_news_item&id=22366 |date=27 May 2011 }}'' from [[Football Federation Australia]], 1 June 2008, retrieved 24 June 2008.</ref> She has also played three matches for the [[Australia women's national under-20 football team|Young Matildas]], the Australian youth team.<ref name=\"unofficial_ym\">[http://users3.jabry.com/auswomensfootball/profile.asp?player=Ellyse%20Perry&team=Young%20Matildas Ellyse Perry Player Profile] from Australian Women's Football unofficial site, retrieved 17 February 2008.</ref>\n\nHer domestic team was the [[Central Coast Mariners W-League|Central Coast Mariners]] in the Australian [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] during the [[W-League 2008\u201309|2008\u201309]] season.<ref name=\"team\">[http://www.ccmariners.com.au/default.aspx?s=wleague_team CCM W-League Team] from Central Coast Mariners, 2008, retrieved 20 November 2008.</ref>\n\nPerry made her debut against [[Queensland Roar W-League|Queensland Roar]] on Saturday, 15 November 2008 after being substituted on for teammate [[Lyndsay Glohe]]. She then went on to play another 2 games, also off the bench.\n\nPerry left the Central Coast Mariners and began playing for [[Canberra United FC|Canberra United]] at the start of the [[2009 W-League (Australia)|2009 W-League]] season.<ref name=\"PerryJoins\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.canberraunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=29542 |title=Perry joins United for 2009 |publisher=Canberra United FC |date=25 September 2009 |accessdate=17 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311084953/http://www.canberraunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=29542 |archivedate=11 March 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt the annual Westfield W-League awards dinner in 2009, Perry was jointly awarded the Young Player of the Year Award with [[Brisbane Roar W-League|Brisbane Roar]]'s [[Elise Kellond-Knight]]<ref name=\"young\">{{Cite web |url=http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/118299,mariner-michelle-scoops-awards.aspx |title=Mariner Michelle Scoops Awards |publisher=FourFourTwo Australia |date=7 December 2009 |accessdate=17 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606230717/http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/118299,mariner-michelle-scoops-awards.aspx |archivedate=6 June 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> and won three club awards for the season \u2013 the Player's, Supporter's and overall Club player of the year.<ref name=sweeps>{{Cite web|url=http://www.canberraunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=31581 |title=Perry sweeps the board at awards |publisher=FourFourTwo Australia |date=21 December 2009 |accessdate=5 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311082319/http://www.canberraunited.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=31581 |archivedate=11 March 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPerry was selected in the Matildas squad for the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/737770 |title=Off-side \u2013 a cricketing XI that made strides in football |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref> In the Norway v Australia group game, Perry came on as a late substitute, and thus became the first Australian woman to represent Australia at a senior World Cup in two different sports, namely cricket and soccer.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} Perry was in the starting line-up for the quarter final against Sweden in which she scored Australia's only goal in the 3\u20131 loss.<ref name=swedengoal/>\n\nAfter being given an ultimatum by Canberra United to either quit cricket or find another [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] club in May 2012, Perry signed with [[Sydney FC W-League|Sydney FC]] for the 2012\u201313 season.<ref name=\"SFC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/sydney-fc-coach-backs-perry-to-play-two-codes-20120905-25e40.html |title=Sydney FC coach backs Perry to play two codes |publisher=Sydney Morning Herald |date=5 September 2012 |accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> Perry noted that Sydney FC was a better fit, as her cricket and university studies were both based in Sydney.\n\nPerry was part of the [[Sydney FC]] squad that competed at the [[2013 International Women's Club Championship]] which comprised women's soccer clubs from Europe, Australia, South America and Japan. Perry played in both of Sydney FC's games. Sydney FC defeated the Japanese Nadeshiko League's runner-up [[NTV Beleza]] 1\u20130, but were beaten 3\u20132 by [[Chelsea L.F.C.]] from the English FA Super League.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/sydney-fc/news/1175321/Sydney-brave-comeback-falls-short |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131204163113/http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/sydney-fc/news/1175321/Sydney-brave-comeback-falls-short |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-12-04 |title=Sydney brave comeback falls short }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/australia/news/1174907/kete-winner-has-sky-blues-flying-high |title=kete winner has sky blues flying high |access-date=4 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206022006/http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/australia/news/1174907/Kete-winner-has-Sky-Blues-flying-high |archive-date=6 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\nPerry scored three international goals during her football career.\n\n''Scores and results list Australia's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=font-size:100%\n|-\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition !! Ref\n|-\n| 1 || 4 August 2007 || [[Mong Kok Stadium]], [[Kowloon]], [[Hong Kong]] || {{fbw|HKG}} || align=\"center\"|'''1'''\u20130 || align=\"center\"|8\u20131 || [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's qualification#AFC (Asia)|2008 Olympics qualifying]] || <ref name=\"matildas_debut\"/>\n|-\n| 2 || 31 May 2008 || [[Th\u1ed1ng Nh\u1ea5t Stadium]], [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]] || {{fbw|KOR}} || align=\"center\"|'''1'''\u20130 || align=\"center\"|2\u20130 || [[2008 AFC Women's Asian Cup]] || <ref name=\"matildas_asian_cup_goal\"/>\n|-\n| 3 || 9 July 2011 || [[WWK ARENA|Impuls Arena]], [[Augsburg]], [[Germany]] || {{fbw|SWE}} || align=\"center\"|'''1'''\u20132 || align=\"center\"|1\u20133 || [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup]] || <ref name=swedengoal>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/41955631 | title = Ellyse Perry: Is there nothing the Australian all-rounder can't do?| date = 11 November 2017 | accessdate = 13 November 2017 | publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Choice of sport==\nBoth football and cricket were keen to retain Perry in their sport. She had accepted in interviews that she would probably one day have to choose between them. After the new Matildas coach took over, the choice was instead made for Perry when she wasn't called up to the National team again.<ref name=\"telegraph\" /><ref name=\"cricinfoTwenty20debut\" /><ref name=\"theage\">''[http://www.theage.com.au/news/sport/two-good-to-be-true/2007/07/14/1183833843299.html Two good to be true]'' from ''[[The Age]]'', 15 July 2007, retrieved 15 February 2008.</ref> In 2010 Perry was faced with the decision whether to play for Australia at the [[ICC World Twenty20]] or at the [[2010 AFC Women's Asian Cup]] which overlapped, of which she chose cricket.\n\nOn 29 May 2012, it was reported that Heather Reid, the chief executive of her football club [[Canberra United FC]], had given Perry an ultimatum to choose between football and cricket.<ref>{{cite news|title=Quit cricket or go: dual international given ultimatum by club |url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/quit-cricket-or-go-dual-international-given-ultimatum-by-club-20120529-1zgkw.html|publisher=theage.com|accessdate=1 June 2012|date=29 May 2012|location=Melbourne}}</ref> On 5 September 2012, Perry signed with Sydney FC,<ref name=\"SFC\" /> with Sydney FC coach Alen Stajcic stating he was prepared to work with NSW Breakers coach Joanne Broadbent to allow Perry to play both sports; however, the co-operation between Sydney FC and NSW Breakers, to enable Perry to play both sports, came to a head when it was reported on 15 January 2013 that Sydney FC's W-League semi-final was scheduled for the same day as the NSW Breakers' Twenty20 final.<ref name=Finals>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/finals-clash-forces-perry-to-play-favourites-20130114-2cpob.html|title=Finals clash forces Perry to play favourites|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> A few days later, Perry's decision was to play in the football semi-final, rather than the Twenty20 cricket final, both of which were to be played on 19 January 2013.<ref name=Decision>{{cite web|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/australia/news/1136956/W-League-Perry-chooses-football|title=W-League: Perry chooses football|work=The World Game|access-date=17 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218055520/http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/australia/news/1136956/W-League-Perry-chooses-football|archive-date=18 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> NSW Breakers won their cricket final, and Sydney too won their football semi-final, but the following weekend for the W-League football Grand Final Perry declined to play for Sydney, opting instead to play for Australia in a warm-up game for the Cricket World Cup in India.<ref name=IndiaWorldCup>[http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/1728930/Perry-to-miss-W-League-grand-final Perry to miss W-League grand final]</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2014, it was reported that Perry elected to play in a W-League semi-final ahead of the national women\u2019s one-day cricket final.<ref name=WLeague>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/ellyse-perry-to-miss-oneday-cricket-final-for-wleague-sydney-fc-semifinal-20140213-32ke3.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Ellyse Perry to miss one-day cricket final for W-League Sydney FC semi-final}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Hesterine de Reus]] took over the role of coach of the Matildas, she indicated that Perry would not be selected for the Australian squad because, with her dual commitments to cricket and football, de Reus felt that Perry was not playing enough football games per year to maintain world-class standard.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/football/ellyse-perrys-dualinternational-career-could-be-over-after-matildas-squad-snub/story-fni2fopz-1226870142867 | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Ellyse Perry\u2019s dual-international career could be over after Matildas squad snub}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Cricket===\n====International====\n;[[Australia women's national cricket team|Australia]]\n* [[Women's Cricket World Cup]]: [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup|2013]]<ref name=WC12/>\n* [[ICC Women's World Twenty20]]: [[2010 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2010]],<ref name=nz/> [[2012 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2012]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8634/game/533313/Australia-Women-vs-England-Women-Final-womens-world-t20 | title = Final, ICC Women's World Twenty20 at Colombo, Oct 7 2012| publisher = ESPNcricinfo| accessdate = 13 November 2017}}</ref> [[2014 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2014]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8634/scorecard/683015/Australia-Women-vs-England-Women-Final-womens-world-t20/| title = Final (D/N), Women's World T20 at Dhaka, Apr 6 2014| publisher = ESPNcricinfo| accessdate = 13 November 2017}}</ref> [[2018 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2018]],[[2020 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2020]].\n\n====Individual====\n*[[Wisden Leading Woman Cricketer in the World|''Wisden'' Leading Woman Cricketer in the World]]: 2016, 2019\n* [[Allan Border Medal#Women's International Cricketer of the Year (Belinda Clark Award)|Belinda Clark Award]]: 2016,<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/> 2018<ref>{{cite news|title=Steve Smith wins his second Allan Border Medal, Ellyse Perry takes out the Belinda Clark Medal|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-02-12/steve-smith-wins-ab-medal-ellyse-perry-takes-belinda-clark-award/9424498?section=sport|accessdate=12 February 2018|publisher=ABC News|date=12 February 2018}}</ref>, 2020\n* Rachael Heyhoe Flint Award for the [[ICC Women's Cricketer of the Year]]: (2017,2019)<ref>{{cite news|title=Ellyse Perry caps incredible 2017 by winning ICC's Women's Cricketer of the Year|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-22/ellyse-perry-named-iccs-womens-cricketer-of-the-year/9280538|accessdate=22 December 2017|work=After a ground-breaking year across all formats, Australia's superstar of the women's game, Ellyse Perry, has won the inaugural Rachael Heyhoe Flint Award from the ICC for Women's Cricketer of the Year.|agency=ABC|date=22 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[ICC Women's Cricketer of the Year|ICC Women's ODI Cricketer of the Year]]: 2019\n*Sport NSW Athlete of the Year: 2019 <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/perry-to-miss-sixers-clash-with-hurricanes-20191118-p53bk5.html|title=Perry named NSW Athlete of the Year hours after sour shoulder diagnosis|last=Phillips|first=Sam|date=18 November 2019|work=Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Soccer===\n====Club====\n;[[Canberra United FC|Canberra United]]\n* [[W-League (Australia)|W-League Premiership]]: [[2011\u201312 W-League|2011\u201312]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-30/perry-to-part-ways-with-canberra-united/4042960 | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] | date = 30 May 2012 | title = Perry looking for new W-League club| accessdate = 13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Individual====\n* [[Canberra United FC|Canberra United]] Player of the Year: [[2009 Canberra United W-League season|2009]]<ref name=sweeps/>\n* [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] Young Player of the Year: [[2009 W-League (Australia)|2009]]<ref name=\"young\"/>\n\n==Books==\n===Non-fiction===\n*''Perspective'' (Sydney: HarperCollins, 2019; {{ISBN|9781460758083}})\n===Children's books===\n*''Pocket Rocket'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 1 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2016; {{ISBN|9780143781240}})\n*''Magic Feet'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 2 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2016; {{ISBN|9780143781264}})\n*''Winning Touch'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 3 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2017; {{ISBN|9780143781288}})\n*''Double Time'' (with Sherryl Clark) Ellyse Perry series, no. 4 (North Sydney: Penguin Random House Australia, 2017; {{ISBN|9780143781301}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{FIFA player|326966}}\n*[http://www.cricket.com.au/players/ellyse-perry/1aMxKNyEOUiJqhq7N5Tlwg Ellyse Perry] at [[Cricket Australia]]\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=275487}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Biography|Cricket|New South Wales|Sports}}\n{{Navboxes\n | title = Links to Ellyse Perry-related articles\n | titlestyle = background: gold; color: green\n | list =\n{{100 WODI wickets}}\n{{Australian Woman Cricketer of the Year}}\n{{Wisden Leading Woman Cricketer in the World}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Australia Squads (Cricket)\n|bg = #FFD700\n|fg = #008000\n|list1 =\n{{Australia Squad 2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Australia Squad 2010 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2012 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2014 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2016 Women's Cricket World T20}}\n{{Australia Squad 2017 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Australia Squad 2018 ICC Women's World Twenty20}}\n{{Sydney Sixers 2017\u20132018 WBBL Champions}}\n{{Loughborough Lightning (cricket)}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Australia Squads (Soccer)\n|bg = #FFE605\n|fg = #005800\n|list1 =\n{{Australia squad 2008 AFC Women's Asian Cup}}\n{{Australia Squad 2011 Women's World Cup}}\n}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Ellyse}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:2011 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Australian women cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia women Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia women One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia women Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australian women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australia women's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Central Coast Mariners FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:Canberra United FC players]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Loughborough Lightning (WCSL) cricketers]]\n[[Category:New South Wales Breakers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Sydney Sixers (WBBL) cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sydney FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:W-League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football defenders]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pymble Ladies' College]]\n", "name_user": "The Rambling Man", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellyse_Perry"}
{"title_page": "Pervez Hoodbhoy", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Pervez Hoodbhoy\n| image = Hoodbhoy.jpg\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|07|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh|Sindh Province]], [[West Pakistan]]\n| residence = [[Islamabad]], [[Islamabad Capital Territory]], [[Pakistan]]\n| fields = [[Physics]]\n| workplaces = [[Quaid-e-Azam University]]<br>[[National Center for Physics]]<br>[[Forman Christian College|FC College University]]<br>[[Virtual University of Pakistan]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT)\n| known_for = [[Parton distribution functions]], [[Field theory (mathematics)|Field Theory]], [[Phenomenology (particle physics)|Phenomenology]], [[supersymmetry]] and [[Abstract algebra]]\n| influences = [[Abdus Salam]], [[George Bernard Shaw]],<ref name=\"old.drsohail.com\">{{cite web |url=http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716211940/http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |archivedate=16 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }} Dr. Sohail Interview, Retrieved 29 March 2012</ref> [[Bertrand Russell]]<ref>{{cite web|title=How Difficult it is to Help People Change their Thinking \u2013 Interview with Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy|url=http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm|accessdate=31 December 2013|author=Dr. K. Sohail|date=February 2000|quote=Pervez: \"I started reading the plays of Bernard Shaw and later on, the works of Bertrand Russell. That had such an impact on me that it bowled me over and by the time I was 15, I was lost, lost to \"all good things\".\"|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716211940/http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm|archivedate=16 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| awards = [[Kalinga Prize|UNESCO Kalinga Prize]] (2003)<br>[[Fulbright Award]] (1998)<br>[[Faiz Ahmed Faiz|Faiz Ahmed Faiz Award]] (1990)<br>[[Abdus Salam Award]] (1984)\n}}\n'''Pervez Amirali Hoodbhoy''' ([[Urdu]]: {{nastaliq|\u067e\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0632 \u06c1\u0648\u062f\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0626\u06cc}}; born 11 July 1950) is a Pakistani [[nuclear physicist]] and [[Activism|activist]] who serves as ''[http://www.fccollege.edu.pk/member/dr-pervez-amirali-hoodbhoy/ Zohra and ZZ Ahmed Foundation distinguished professor]'' at the [[Forman Christian College University|Forman Christian College]] and previously taught physics at the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]].<ref name=\"Forman College University Press\">{{cite web|last1=FCC University|title=Faculty of Physics at FCC University|url=http://www.fccollege.edu.pk/faculty-directory/university-faculty/physics|website=fccollege.edu.pk|publisher=Forman College University Press|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dr Hoodbhoy at FCC|url = http://nation.com.pk/business/12-Sep-2013/dr-hoodbhoy-at-fcc|website = The Nation|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref> Hoodbhoy is also a prominent [[political activist|activist]] in particular concerned with promotion of [[freedom of speech]], [[Secularism in Pakistan|secularism]] and [[Education in Pakistan|education]] in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1546317/corona-our-debt-to-darwin|title=Corona \u2014 our debt to Darwin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/national/14-Apr-2003/muslims-must-stop-glorifying-terrorism-hoodbhoy| title = Muslims must stop glorifying terrorism: Hoodbhoy| website = DailyTimes| access-date = 2016-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://thediplomat.com/2015/11/interview-pervez-hoodbhoy/| title = Interview: Pervez Hoodbhoy| last = Diplomat| first = Muhammad Akbar Notezai, The| website = The Diplomat| access-date = 2016-02-27}}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[Karachi]], Hoodbhoy studied at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] for nine years, where he received degrees in electrical engineering, mathematics and [[solid-state physics]], eventually leading to a [[PhDs|PhD]] in [[nuclear physics]]. In 1981, Hoodbhoy went on to conduct [[Postdoctoral researcher|post-doctoral]] research at the [[University of Washington]], before leaving to serve as a [[Visiting scholar|visiting professor]] at the [[Carnegie Mellon University]] in 1985. While still a professor at the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]], Hoodbhoy worked as a guest scientist at the [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics]] between 1986 until 1994. He remained with the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]] until 2010, throughout which he held visiting professorships at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] and [[Stanford Linear Collider]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eacpe.org/content/uploads/2014/02/PH-CV-2013.pdf|title=Curriculum vitae for Pervez Amirali Hoodbhoy|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Hoodbhoy joined [[Lahore University of Management Sciences|LUMS]] while simultaneously working as a researcher with the [[Princeton University]] and a columnist with the ''[[Express Tribune]]''. His contract with LUMS was terminated in 2013 which resulted in a controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/458332/the-pervez-hoodbhoy-lums-dispute/|title=The Pervez Hoodbhoy-LUMS dispute \u2013 The Express Tribune|date=2012-10-30|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref> He is a sponsor of the ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'', and a member of the monitoring panel on terrorism of the World Federation of Scientists.<ref>{{Cite web|title = PMP \u2013 Terrorism|url = http://www.federationofscientists.org/pmpanels/terrorism/Terrorism.asp|website = www.federationofscientists.org|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> Hoodbhoy has won several awards including the [[Abdus Salam]] [[Abdus Salam Award|Prize]] for Mathematics (1984);<ref>{{Cite web|title = About Pervez Hoodbhoy|url = http://eacpe.org/about-pervez-hoodbhoy/|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> the [[Kalinga Prize]] for the popularization of science (2003);<ref>{{Cite web|title = Kalinga award for Dr Hoodbhoy|url = http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/national/31-Oct-2003/kalinga-award-for-dr-hoodbhoy|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> the [[Burton Awards for Legal Achievement|Burton Award]] (2010)<ref>{{Cite web|title = Prize Recipient|url = http://www.aps.org/programs/honors/prizes/prizerecipient.cfm?last_nm=Hoodbhoy&first_nm=Pervez&year=2010|website = www.aps.org|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> from the [[American Physical Society]]. In 2011, he was included in the list of 100 most influential global thinkers by ''[[Foreign Policy]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The FP Top 100 Global Thinkers|url = https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/11/28/the-fp-top-100-global-thinkers-3/|website = Foreign Policy|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, he was made a member of the UN Secretary General's Advisory Board on Disarmament.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Secretary-General Appoints Replacements for Outgoing Members of Advisory Board on Disarmament Matters {{!}} Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|url = https://www.un.org/press/en/2012/dc3407.doc.htm|website = www.un.org|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHoodbhoy remains one of Pakistan's most prominent academics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1234746|title=Back from the enemy country|first=Pervez|last=Hoodbhoy|date=23 January 2016|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref> He is the author of ''Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality''<ref>{{Cite book|title = Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality|url = https://books.google.com/?id=RKSyQgAACAAJ|publisher = Zed Books|date = 1 January 1991|isbn = 9781856490245|first = Pervez|last = Hoodbhoy}}</ref> He is the head of ''Mashal'' Books in Lahore, which claims to make \"a major translation effort to produce books in Urdu that promote modern thought, human rights, and emancipation of women\". Hoodbhoy has written for ''[[Project Syndicate]]'', [[DAWN (newspaper)|''DAWN'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1402940|title=What India owes to Nehru|first=Pervez|last=Hoodbhoy|date=21 April 2018|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1496468|title=Pakistan\u2019s slice of the moon|first=Pervez|last=Hoodbhoy|date=27 July 2019|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Express Tribune]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Pervez Hoodbhoy \u2013 Project Syndicate|url = http://www.project-syndicate.org/columnist/pervez-hoodbhoy|website = www.project-syndicate.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Pakistan, the Saudis' Indispensable Nuclear Partner|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/22/opinion/toward-a-saudi-pakistani-rift.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2015-04-21|access-date = 2016-02-17|issn = 0362-4331|first = Pervez|last = Hoodbhoy}}</ref> Hoodbhoy is generally considered one of the most vocal, progressive and liberal member of the Pakistani [[intelligentsia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/19373/calling-dr-pervez-hoodbhoy-jahil-can-only-happen-in-pakistan/|title=Calling Dr Pervez Hoodbhoy 'jahil' can only happen in Pakistan|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref> His daughter, [[Alia Amirali]], is also a well-known feminist and political activist.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn and raised in [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], Hoodbhoy passed the competitive [[O-Level]] and [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]] exams after attending the famed [[Karachi Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716211940/http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |archivedate=16 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> After earning a scholarship, Hoodbhoy went to the United States to attend the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT).<ref name=\"Geo News\">{{cite episode| title =A Day with Geo: Interview with Pervez Hoodbhoy| episodelink =| url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MmzoYZjFEJE| series =| serieslink =| credits =| network =Geo News| station =| location =Islamabad| airdate =28 April 2011| began =| ended =| season =| seriesno =| number =| minutes =30:00| transcript =| transcripturl= }}</ref> While attending the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] in [[Massachusetts]], Hoodbhoy worked for a local [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistani restaurant]] based in [[Massachusetts]] to support his studies and showed a great interest in [[Electronic engineering|electronics]] and mathematics.<ref>http://www.newslinemagazine.com/2012/08/interview-dr-pervez-hoodbhoy/</ref>\n\nAt [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], Hoodbhoy graduated with [[double major|double]] BSc in [[Electrical Engineering]] and mathematics in 1971, followed by MS in [[physics]] with a concentration in [[solid-state physics]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Global Zero\">{{Cite web|title =Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy | work =Global Zero | publisher=Global Zero | url =http://www.globalzero.org/en/who/pervez-hoodbhoy | doi = | accessdate =January 1, 2011}}</ref> After graduation, Hoodbhoy joined the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]] (QAU) as a researcher and renewed his scholarship to resume his studies in the United States.<ref name=\"Geo TV\" />\n\nHoodbhoy continued his research in doctoral studies in [[physics]] at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], and was awarded PhD in [[nuclear physics]] in 1978.<ref name=\"Geo TV\"/> In the United States, his collaboration took place with the [[:Category:Manhattan Project people|scientists]] who participated in well known [[Manhattan Project]] in the 1940s, who subsequently influenced in his philosophy.<ref name=\"Geo TV\">{{Cite video\n | people =Parvez Hood Bhoy\n | title =ADGKS Parvez Hood Bhoy 187605 C1.mp4\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgENuWF7blM&feature=channel\n | medium =Television Production\n | publisher =Geo TV\n | location =\n | date =2010 }}\n</ref> Hoodbhoy remained a post-doctoral research fellow at the [[University of Washington]], for a short time.<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/> In 1973, Hoodbhoy joined the [[Pakistan Institute of Physics|Institute of Physics]] of the [[University of Engineering and Technology, Lahore|University of Engineering and Technology]] in [[Lahore]].<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Academia ===\nHoodbhoy focused his research career extensively on [[quantum field theory]], [[Phenomenology (particle physics)|particle phenomenology]], and [[supersymmetry]] in the area of [[particle physics]].<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/> After receiving PhD from [[MIT]], Hoodbhoy met [[Riazuddin (physicist)|Riazuddin]] and [[Abdus Salam]]\u2013 the prominent Pakistani physicists who were visiting the [[MIT]] to give lectures on particle physics. Subsequently, he joined the group of Pakistani physicists at the [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics]] in [[Trieste, Italy|Trieste]], Italy.<ref name=\"Hoodbhoy\"/> At [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics|ICTP]], Hoodbhoy collaborated with Pakistan's leading theoretical physicists who worked under [[Abdus Salam]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"Hoodbhoy\">{{Cite web | last =Hoodbhoy | first =Pervez | title =Fascinating encounters: Prof Abdus Salam | publisher =Hoodbhoy | url =http://www.globalwebpost.com/farooqm/study_res/abdus_salam/encounter.html | accessdate =January 1, 2011 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150924022536/http://www.globalwebpost.com/farooqm/study_res/abdus_salam/encounter.html | archivedate =24 September 2015 | df =dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics|ICTP]] work, Hoodbhoy returned to Pakistan to join [[Quaid-e-Azam University]] (QAU) where he began teaching and lecturing on physics. Eventually, he became chairman of [[Institute of Theoretical Physics, Qau|Institute of Theoretical Physics]] (now department of physics). After spending more than 30 years at [[Quaid-e-Azam University|Qau]], Hoodbhoy moved to [[Lahore]] where he joined the [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]] as a visiting professor, while remains a visiting scientist at the [[Stanford Linear Accelerator Center]].<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/> Controversy over his contract in [[Lahore University of Management Sciences|LUMS]] sparked an academic debate when it was reported in the [[Pakistani media|news media]] that Hoodbhoy's email to [[Vice-Chancellor]] of [[Lahore University of Management Sciences|LUMS]] was made public.<ref name=\"Express Tribune, 2012\">{{cite news|last1=Shaukat|first1=Aroosa|title=LUMS vs Hoodbhoy: I'm losing job for 'ideological reasons', says professor|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/456391/lums-vs-hoodbhoy-im-losing-job-for-ideological-reasons-says-professor/|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Express Tribune|publisher=Express Tribune, 2012|date=25 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Express Tribune\">{{cite news|last1=Haider|first1=Ejaz|title=The Pervez Hoodbhoy-LUMS dispute|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/458332/the-pervez-hoodbhoy-lums-dispute/|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Express Tribune|newspaper=Express Tribune|date=30 October 2012}}</ref> Eventually, Hoodbhoy moved to [[Forman Christian College University]] permanently and joined the senior staff to instructed courses on physics.<ref name=\"Forman College University Press\" />\n\nPrior to his return to Pakistan in 1976, the secretive development program on [[Pakistan and its Nuclear Deterrent Program|nuclear deterrence]] was near completion and Hoodbhoy was aware of the program.<ref name=\"Newsweek, 2013\">{{cite news|last1=Hoodbhoy|first1=Pervez|title=The Man Who Designed Pakistan's Bomb|url=http://newsweekpakistan.com/|accessdate=13 February 2015|work=Special biographical article in the honor of Dr. Riazuddin|agency=Newsweek|publisher=Newsweek, 2013|date=30 November 2013|archiveurl=http://newsweekpakistan.com/the-man-who-designed-pakistans-bomb/.|archivedate=30 November 2013|location=Islamabad, Pakistan|pages=5}}</ref> Hoodbhoy maintains his close ties with Pakistan's vibrant [[Pakistan Nuclear Society|nuclear society]], and had collaborated with many of country's leading theoretical physicists throughout his career, mainly with [[Ishfaq Ahmad]].<ref name=\"Newsweek, 2013\"/> On several occasions, Hoodbhoy staunchly countered Dr. [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]]'s \"father-of\" claims, and roundly criticized his academic research on [[nuclear physics]].<ref name=\"Stanford University Press\">{{cite book|last1=Khan|first1=Feroz Hassan|title=Eating grass : the making of the Pakistani bomb|date=2012|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, Calif.|isbn=978-0804776004}}</ref> In the 1980s, he famously debated with [[Sultan Bashiruddin Mahmood|Bashiruddin Mahmood]] on the topics of [[sunspots]], [[Life After Death|life-after-death]], and philosophy.<ref name=\"Free Press.\">Bergen, Peter L. (2011). \"\u00a7Quixotic Quest\". The longest war : the enduring conflict between America and al-Qaeda (1st Free Press trade paperback edition) New York: Free Press. {{ISBN|0743278941}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Hoodbhoy with [[Ishfaq Ahmad]] and Riazuddin, played a major and influential role in the establishment of [[National Center for Physics]] (NCP), becoming one of the earliest academic scientists who joined the NCP at its inception.\n\nHoodbhoy has roundly criticized the development on [[nuclear weapons]], especially its [[Nuclear race|extension]] to South Asia, mainly by [[India and Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\">{{Cite web\n |last=Hoodbhoy, PhD (Nuclear Physics) \n |first=Pervez Amerali \n |title=Pakistan's nuclear bayonet \n |work=Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy, Doctor of Philosophy (Nuclear Physics), Professor of Nuclear and High-Energy Physics at the Quaid-e-Azam University and Senior academic research scientist at the [[National Center for Physics|National Center for Nuclear Physics]] \n |publisher=Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']] \n |date=23 January 2011 \n |url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/02/16/herald-exclusive-pakistans-nuclear-bayonet.html \n |accessdate=9 September 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218212415/http://www.dawn.com/2011/02/16/herald-exclusive-pakistans-nuclear-bayonet.html \n |archivedate=18 February 2011 \n}}</ref> In 2011, Hoodbhoy held India responsible for Pakistan's symmetric [[Pakistan and Nuclear Weapons|nuclear weapons programme]] as part of Pakistan's [[Minimum Credible Deterrence|self-credible deterrence]].<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\" /> According to Hoodbhoy, India's [[Pokhran-I|nuclear tests]] forced Pakistan to jump into the [[Nuclear club|nuclear arena]] in 1974, and again in 1998, after war-threatening statements were made by [[Indian government]] to Pakistan; Pakistan [[Chagai-I|equalised]] this magnitude over the nuclear edge that same month.<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\"/> While believing that Pakistan's [[Pakistan and its Nuclear Deterrent Program|nuclear deterrence]] has protected the country from any [[Foreign interventionism|foreign aggression]] and preventing from numerous [[India Pakistan Wars|war threatening situations]] with India, Hoodbhoy on the other hand has raised concerns about the [[Nuclear safety and security|security]] of [[Pakistan's nuclear weapons|nuclear arsenals]] on the possibility of [[Islamic extremism|radicals]] gaining control.<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\" />\n\n=== Activism ===\nHoodbhoy is a prominent sponsor of the ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'', representing the Pakistan's delegation.<ref>CGPACS (2006) [http://www.socsci.uci.edu/events/060512_hoodbhoy/hoodbhoy6.htm 15th Annual Margolis Lecture with Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy]. The Center for Global Peace and Conflict Studies. [[University of California, Irvine]]. 12 May. Retrieved on 22 May 2008</ref>\n\nApart from his specialist field of research, Hoodbhoy extensively writes and speaks on topics ranging from [[Islamic sciences|science]] in [[Islam]] to [[Education in Pakistan|education]] and [[nuclear disarmament|arms disarmament]] issues around the world.<ref>Hoodbhoy (1998) [http://www.cs.ucsb.edu/~acha/politics/hoodbhoy.html Talk by Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy on nuclear tests in the Indian subcontinent]. The Alliance, Pakistan Students Society at MIT, and the MIT Program in Science, Technology, and Society. 12 May. Retrieved on 22 May 2008</ref> He is author of ''Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality'', that has been translated into five languages.<ref name=\"Fulbright Program\">{{Cite web   |last = (FPS)|first = Fulbright Scholar Program|authorlink = Fulbright Program|title = U.S. and Non U.S. Scholar: Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy|work = Global Zero|publisher = Fulbright Program|year = 2007|url = http://www.cies.org/NCS/2007_2008/scholars/ncs_phoodbhoy.htm|doi = |accessdate = January 1, 2011}}</ref> In this book, Hoodbhoy outlines the [[History of Pakistan|history]] of Pakistan, implications of [[theocracy]] and [[Martial law in Pakistan|martial law]] in Pakistan, and the [[Pakistani textbooks controversy|textbook revival]] in education system of Pakistan. His articles on various issues related to science and [[social issues]] are often published in international media. His publications are repeatedly published in both technical and non-technical papers.\n{{Quote box\n |title = \n |quote = Though I know that it is not welcome in my country and people who deviate from the notion that it is an Islamic state, are looked upon disapprovingly, I strongly feel that's what we need to head towards.\n |source = [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Pak-was-born-in-a-state-of-confusion-Hoodbhoy/articleshow/50516062.cms Talking to the Hyderabad Literary Festival]\n |align=right\n |width=30%\n}}\n[[File:Solidarity message to ex-Muslims - Pervez Hoodbhoy.webm|thumb|Pervez Hoodbhoy criticises Pakistani attitudes on \"[[blasphemy]]\".]]\nHoodbhoy widely writes about the role and modernisation of [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistan military]], particularly the defence budget spending by the [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistan government]] on the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|military]]. In an interview on [[secularism]], he mentioned that obsession with scientific-religious [[apophenia]] may have caused lack of scientific advancement among [[Muslim world|Muslims]] in recent years.<ref>[http://www.meforum.org/2593/pervez-amirali-hoodbhoy-islam-science Pervez Amirali Hoodbhoy: \"Islam and Science Have Parted Ways\"]; Interview in ''Middle East Quarterly''; Winter 2010, pp. 69\u201374, Retrieved 2 March 2012</ref> In 2003 he was one the signers of the [[Humanism and Its Aspirations|Humanist Manifesto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanhumanist.org/Humanism/Humanist_Manifesto_III/Notable_Signers |title=Notable Signers |publisher=American Humanist Association |work=Humanism and Its Aspirations |accessdate=6 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005105825/http://www.americanhumanist.org/Humanism/Humanist_Manifesto_III/Notable_Signers |archivedate=5 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHoodbhoy has criticized the Pakistan [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|Higher Education Commission]] (HEC) for pursuing \"a drive to achieve numbers rather than quality\".<ref name=\"Shehzad\">{{cite news|last1=Shehzad|first1=Rizwan|title=Hoodbhoy feels restructuring better than saving old HEC|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/483217/hoodbhoy-feels-restructuring-better-than-saving-old-hec/|accessdate=1 July 2015|agency=Tribune.com.pk|date=23 December 2012}}</ref> He believes that because of \"policies that reward authors of research articles and PhD supervisors with cash and promotions\", universities in Pakistan have \"turned into factories producing junk papers and PhDs.\"<ref name=\"HOODBHOY-29-11-14\">{{cite news|last1=Hoodbhoy|first1=Pervez|title=Misjudging universities|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1147559|accessdate=1 July 2015|agency=Dawn|date=29 November 2014}}</ref>\nHe has been a harsh critic on the performance of [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]] since 2003 when it was led by Dr. [[Atta ur Rahman (scientist)|Atta-ur-Rahman]], and the issue has led to heated debates in Pakistan's [[News channels in Pakistan|news media]].<ref name=\"Pakistaniaat\" />\n\nIn 2009 Hoodbhoy came into conflict with [[Atta ur Rahman (scientist)|Atta-ur-Rahman]], an [[Organic Chemistry|organic chemist]], over the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|Higher Education Commission]] (HEC). In the United States, the journal [[Nature (journal)|''Nature'']] published an article on the successes and failures of the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]].<ref name=\"Pakistaniat, 2009\">{{cite web|last1=Najam|first1=Adil|title=Pakistan in Higher Education|url=http://pakistaniat.com/2009/09/03/nature-pakistan-higher-education/|publisher=Pakistaniat, 2009|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> Hoodbhoy wrote to complain about, among other things, the article's failure to mention (what Hoodbhoy called) \"the billions wasted on mindless prestige mega-projects\".<ref name=\"Pakistaniaat\" />\nIn the debate on [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]] [[Adil Najam]], [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]], and [[Atta ur Rahman (scientist)|Atta-ur-Rehman]] defended the HEC while agreeing with some of Hoodbhoy's criticism.<ref name=\"Pakistaniaat\">{{cite news|last1=Najam |first1=Adil |title=Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy Responds to Nature Article on Pakistan's Higher Education Reform |url=http://pakistaniat.com/2009/09/05/hoodbhoy-nature-pakistan-education-reform/ |accessdate=13 February 2015 |agency=Pakistaniaat |publisher=Pakistaniaat |date=9 September 2009 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626160300/http://pakistaniat.com/2009/09/05/hoodbhoy-nature-pakistan-education-reform/ |archivedate=26 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAdministrative competency of [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]] was called into question by Hoodbhoy who describe the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]]'s achievement \"dismal\".<ref name=\"Dawn newspapers, 2012\">{{cite news|last1=Hassan|first1=Shazia|title=HEC lost track by focusing on quantity rather than quality'|url=http://dawn.com/news/773021/hec-lost-track-by-focusing-on-quantity-rather-than-quality|accessdate=13 February 2015|agency=Dawn newspapers, 2012|publisher=Dawn newspapers, 2012|date=12 December 2012}}</ref> Hoodbhoy supported his arguments against [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]]'s productivity, that in the case of [[Lille University of Science and Technology|UESTP-France]] convention in [[Karachi]], out of an expected faculty strength of between 450 and 600, no French faculty or administrative staff actually arrived.<ref name=\"Dawn newspapers, 2012\" /> At the television debate, Hoodbhoy questioned the statistics used to support the positive appraisal of HEC's activities in a series of communications between Hoodbhoy and HEC chairman Atta-Ur-Rehman.<ref>{{cite web|title=HEC's performance by Atta ur Rehman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TYiNGvfbM-A|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoodbhoy|title=The HEC {{sic|nolink=y|Controvery}}- Separating Fact and fiction|url=https://vimeo.com/61231182|website=Vimeo}}</ref> It was claimed by the latter that in mathematics, Pakistani authors received 20% more citations than the worldwide average. Hoodbhoy questioned this on several grounds including the number of self-citations these publications received and said that this was a crucial aspect that the HEC left out of its interpretation. Criticism was leveled by Hoodbhoy at the practice of hiring those foreign academics in local universities who were said to have difficulty in communicating and teaching, although they contributed to boosting the number of research publications originating from Pakistani universities.\n\n=== Research ===\nHoodbhoy has made important contributions in physics, particularly in particle physics. Many of Hoodbhoy's recorded lectures on physics are available online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://urduphysicslectures.blogspot.com/|title=General Physics Lectures In English}}</ref> At [[National Center for Physics]], Hoodbhoy conducted research on different aspects of particle physics, and pioneered studies in modern physics and its extension to mathematical and nuclear physics. In 2006, Hoodbhoy published a brief mathematical description of [[Generalized Parton Distributions]]. In 2007, Hoodbhoy re-published the work of Jens Lyng Peterson the [[AdS/CFT correspondence|Maldacena conjecture]] (a conjectured equivalence between a string theory and gravity defined on one space, and a quantum field theory without gravity defined by one or less dimension) where he contributed mathematically to the theory.<ref>{{Cite conference | first =Jens Lyng | last =Peterson | authorlink = |author2=Dr. Prof. Pervez Hoodbhoy | title=Introduction to Maldacena conjecture | pages=41| publisher =Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy of National Center for Physics; Second National Winter Meeting on Particles and Fields and Jens Lyng Peterson | date = 28\u201331 December 2009 | location =Islamabad, Islamabad Capital Territory | url=http://www.ncp.edu.pk/docs/snwm/Pervez_hoodbhoy_003_Intro_to_Maldacena_Conjecture.pdf | doi = | accessdate =January 1, 2011 }}</ref> In the same year, he re-published the work of [[Edward Witten]] on [[Anti-de Sitter space]] and its extension to the field of [[Holography]]. While the paper was published experimentally in 1998 by Witten, Hoodbhoy provided the brief mathematical proofs and description to understand, logically, the subject of Sitter space\u2014 a [[scalar curvature]] in general theory of relativity.<ref>{{Cite conference | first=Dr. Prof. Edward | last=Witten | authorlink =Edward Witten |author2=Dr. Prof. Pervez Hoodbhoy | title =Anti de Sitter Space and Holography|pages =41| publisher=Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy of National Center for Physics; Second National Winter Meeting on Particles and Fields and Edward Witten (1998)| date = 28\u201331 December 2009 | location =Islamabad, Islamabad Capital Territory |url=http://www.ncp.edu.pk/docs/snwm/Pervez_hoodbhoy_004_Holography_Witten.pdf | doi = | accessdate=January 1, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April 2001, it was announced that Dr. Hoodbhoy would be receiving [[Sitara-e-Imtiaz|''Sitara-i-Imtiaz'']] from the former [[President of Pakistan|President]], General (retired) [[Pervez Musharraf]] which he refused to accept. His refusal prompted the [[The Friday Times|''Friday Times'']] to interview him.\n\n{{quote|text=I am reasonably [satisfied] with my (scientific) work... I do not think it is earth-shaking or... that it deserves any kind of [award]. On the other hand, receiving an [award] \u2013 even if it is a high national award \u2013 would give me absolutely no sense of achievement or satisfaction... because it carries no credibility or prestige in professional circles. Such things do not indicate that you have done good work in your field. Therefore I decided to refuse the award.|sign=Pervez Hoodbhoy, <small>issued the statement on ''The Friday Times'', 2001</small>|source=<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hoodbhoy|first=Pervez|date=23 April 2001|url=http://www.chowk.com/articles/5034|title=Refusing The Sitara-I-Imtiaz|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121155705/http://chowk.com/articles/5034}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Filmography ===\nHe produced a 13-part documentary series in [[Urdu]] for [[Pakistan Television]] on critical issues in education, and two series aimed at popularising science. In 2004, he made a documentary film '[[Crossing the Lines]]: Kashmir, Pakistan, India' along with Dr. [[Zia Mian]].<ref>CGPACS (2006) [http://www.socsci.uci.edu/files/socsci/announcements/060512_hoodbhoy/crossingthelines.htm Crossing the Lines: Kashmir, Pakistan, India]</ref> These documentaries carry heavy emphasis on the issues of education, public health and scientific revolution in Pakistan.\n\nIn his documentaries, Dr. Hoodbhoy has heavily criticised Pakistan and India's nuclear weapons program. He also pointed out the seriousness of the Talibanization in Pakistan and its immediate effects on South Asia. His documentaries also point out that American and [[NATO]] forces in Afghanistan didn't help the Afghan people's life and there was no reform in Afghanistan's social and public sector and, instead, the insurgency and corruption grew, which also destabilised Pakistan's western front.<ref name=\"Fulbright Program\"/>\n* ''Crossing the Lines: Kashmir, Pakistan, India'' (2004)\n* ''The Bell Tolls for Planet Earth'' (2003)\n* ''Pakistan and India Under the Nuclear Shadow'' (2001)\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Education and the State: Fifty Years Of Pakistan'' [[Oxford University Press]], 1998. {{ISBN|978-0-19-577825-0}}\n* ''Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality'' Zed Books, London, 1992. {{ISBN|978-1-85649-025-2}}, (Translations in [[Arabic]], [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], [[Malay language|Malaysian]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], Japanese, and [[Urdu]])\n* (Co-Edited with A. Ali), ''Proceedings of the School on Fundamental Physics and Cosmology'' World Scientific, Singapore, 1991.\n* (With [[A H Nayyar|A. H. Nayyar]]), \"Rewriting the History of Pakistan\", in ''Islam, Politics and the State: The Pakistan Experience'', Ed. Mohammad Asghar Khan, Zed Books, London, 1986. {{ISBN|978-0-86232-471-1}}\n\n===Scientific papers and articles===\n* Two-Photon Effects in Lepton-AntiLepton Pair Photoproduction from a Nucleon Target using Real Photons, Authors: Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 73 (2006) 054027\n* Probing Quark Distribution Amplitudes Through Generalized Parton Distributions at Large Momentum Transfer, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Feng Yuan, Phys. Rev. Lett. 92 (2004) 012003\n* Explicit Proof that Electroproduction of Transversely Polarized Vector Mesons Vanishes in Perturbative QCD, Pervez Hoodbhoy (University of Maryland and Quaid-e-Azam University), Phys. Rev. D 65 (2002) 077501\n* Does the Gluon Spin Contribute in A Gauge Invariant Way to Nucleon Spin? Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Phys. Rev. D 60 (1999) 114042\n* Nucleon-Quarkonium Elastic Scattering and the Gluon Contribution to Nucleon Spin, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. Lett. 82 (1999) 4985\u20134987\n* Implications of Color Gauge Symmetry For Nucleon Spin Structure, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Wei Lu, Phys. Rev. D 59 (1999) 074010\n* Quark Orbital-Angular-Momentum Distribution in the Nucleon, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Wei Lu, Phys. Rev. D 59 (1999) 014013\n* Helicity-Flip Off-Forward Parton Distributions of the Nucleon, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Phys. Rev. D 58 (1998) 054006\n* Wavefunction corrections and off-forward gluon distributions in diffractive J/psi electroproduction, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 56 (1997) 388\u2013393\n* Relativistic and Binding Energy Corrections to Direct Photon Production In Upsilon Decay, Mohammad Ali Yusuf, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 54 (1996) 3345\u20133349\n* Beyond The Colour-Singlet Model For Inelastic J_psi Photoproduction, H. Khan, P. Hoodbhoy, Phys. Lett. B382 (1996) 189\n* The Spin Structure of the Nucleon in the Asymptotic Limit, X. Ji, J. Tang (MIT), P. Hoodbhoy (Quaid-e-Azam, Pakistan), Phys. Rev. Lett. 76 (1996) 740\u2013743\n* Novel approach to decays, gluon distributions, and fragmentation functions of heavy quarkonia, Rafia Ali, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 51 (1995) 2302\u20132310\n* Quark fragmentation functions in a diquark model for proton and $\\Lambda$ hyperon production, Muhammad Nzar, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 51 (1995) 32\u201336\n* Systematic gauge invariant approach to heavy quarkonium decays, Hafsa Khan, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 53 (1996) 2534\u20132540\n* Twist-Four Distributions in a Transversely-Polarized Nucleon and the Drell-Yan Process, Pevrez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Xi, Phys. Rev. D 50 (1994) 4429\u20134435\n* Detecting Two-Photon Exchange Effects in Hard Scattering from Nucleon Targets, in [[Mathematical Physics]]: Proceedings of the 12th Regional Conference, Islamabad, Pakistan 27 March \u2013 1 April 2006, World Scientific, Singapore, 2007. {{ISBN|978-981-270-591-4}}\n* Abdus Salam: Past and Present- The News (29 January 1996)\n* [http://www.ncp.edu.pk/docs/12th_rgdocs/Pervez-Hoodbhoy.pdf Generalized Parton Distributions], Pervez Hoodbhoy, Quaid-e-Azam University, Islamabad\n\n==Appearances in TV shows==\n* ''Raaste Ilm ke'' (Pathways to Knowledge) on [[PTV Home|PTV]], 1988\n* ''Asrar-e-Jahan'' (Mysteries of the Universe) on [[PTV Home|PTV]], 1995\n* ''Bazm-e-Kainat'' (Gathering of all Creation)  on [[PTV Home|PTV]], 2003\n* ''Alif'' on Geo TV. Debate with Jawed Ghamidi, 2006\n* ''Aik Din Geo Kay Saath'' on [[Geo TV]], February 2010\n* ''Capital Talk'' on [[Geo TV]], 29 August 2012\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{in lang|de}} Kaznain, Hazim. \"[http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/interview-mit-dem-pakistanischen-atomphysiker-pervez-hoodbhoy-a-879319.html Pakistanischer Atomphysiker: \"Muslimische Gesellschaften sind kollektiv gescheitert]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6XSb5PCI6?url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/interview-mit-dem-pakistanischen-atomphysiker-pervez-hoodbhoy-a-879319.html Archive]). ''[[Der Spiegel]]''. Monday 28 January 2013. Interview with Hoodbhoy.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.simloo.com A complete repository of Pervez Hoodbhoy's articles in the making]\n* [http://www.qau.edu.pk/profile.php?id=yLn9T Profile], QAU\n* [http://www.zmag.org/zspace/search/znetarticles/pervezhoodbhoy Pervez Hoodbhoy's recent articles for Z Magazine]\n* [http://www.chowk.com/show_writer_page.cgi?pen_name=Pervez%20Hoodbhoy Pervez Hoodbhoy's articles for the website Chowk.com]\n* [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Pervez+Hoodbhoy&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en&btnG=Search Pervez Hoodbhoy's research papers]\n* [http://ptonline.aip.org/journals/doc/PHTOAD-ft/vol_60/iss_8/49_1.shtml Science and the Islamic world\u2014The quest for rapprochement], Pervez Hoodbhoy, [[American Institute of Physics]], August 2007\n* [http://cgs.illinois.edu/resources/webvideo/sacred-terror-theirs-and-ours Video Presentation:] \"Sacred Terror: Theirs and Ours.\" Professor Hoodbhoy speaking at the University of Illinois, October 2007.\n* [http://www.himalmag.com/Pakistan-s-westward-drift_nw1947.html Pakistan's westward drift] \u2013 article by P Hoodbhoy lamenting the rising tide of [[militant Islam]] in Pakistan\n* [http://www.prospect-magazine.co.uk/article_details.php?id=4244 Islamic Failure] \u2013 2002 article by P Hoodbhoy, first published in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and reprinted in ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoodbhoy, Pervez Amirali}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Pakistani physicists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Ismailis]]\n[[Category:Pakistani democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani educators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani scientists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani scholars]]\n[[Category:Pakistani science writers]]\n[[Category:Kalinga Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lahore University of Management Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani anti\u2013nuclear weapons activists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:Quaid-i-Azam University faculty]]\n[[Category:Pakistani anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:Karachi Grammar School alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani humanists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani science journalists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani secularists]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pakistan Philosophical Congress]]\n[[Category:MIT Department of Physics alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Pervez Hoodbhoy\n| image = Hoodbhoy.jpg\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|07|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh|Sindh Province]], [[West Pakistan]]\n| residence = [[Islamabad]], [[Islamabad Capital Territory]], [[Pakistan]]\n| fields = [[Physics]]\n| workplaces = [[Quaid-e-Azam University]]<br>[[National Center for Physics]]<br>[[Forman Christian College|FC College University]]<br>[[Virtual University of Pakistan]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT)\n| known_for = [[Parton distribution functions]], [[Field theory (mathematics)|Field Theory]], [[Phenomenology (particle physics)|Phenomenology]], [[supersymmetry]] and [[Abstract algebra]]\n| influences = [[Abdus Salam]], [[George Bernard Shaw]],<ref name=\"old.drsohail.com\">{{cite web |url=http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716211940/http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |archivedate=16 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }} Dr. Sohail Interview, Retrieved 29 March 2012</ref> [[Bertrand Russell]]<ref>{{cite web|title=How Difficult it is to Help People Change their Thinking \u2013 Interview with Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy|url=http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm|accessdate=31 December 2013|author=Dr. K. Sohail|date=February 2000|quote=Pervez: \"I started reading the plays of Bernard Shaw and later on, the works of Bertrand Russell. That had such an impact on me that it bowled me over and by the time I was 15, I was lost, lost to \"all good things\".\"|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716211940/http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm|archivedate=16 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| awards = [[Kalinga Prize|UNESCO Kalinga Prize]] (2003)<br>[[Fulbright Award]] (1998)<br>[[Faiz Ahmed Faiz|Faiz Ahmed Faiz Award]] (1990)<br>[[Abdus Salam Award]] (1984)\n}}\n'''Pervez Amirali Hoodbhoy''' ([[Urdu]]: {{nastaliq|\u067e\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0632 \u06c1\u0648\u062f\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0626\u06cc}}; born 11 July 1950) is a Pakistani [[nuclear physicist]] and [[Activism|activist]] who serves as ''[http://www.fccollege.edu.pk/member/dr-pervez-amirali-hoodbhoy/ Zohra and ZZ Ahmed Foundation distinguished professor]'' at the [[Forman Christian College University|Forman Christian College]] and previously taught physics at the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]].<ref name=\"Forman College University Press\">{{cite web|last1=FCC University|title=Faculty of Physics at FCC University|url=http://www.fccollege.edu.pk/faculty-directory/university-faculty/physics|website=fccollege.edu.pk|publisher=Forman College University Press|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dr Hoodbhoy at FCC|url = http://nation.com.pk/business/12-Sep-2013/dr-hoodbhoy-at-fcc|website = The Nation|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref> Hoodbhoy is also a prominent [[political activist|activist]] in particular concerned with promotion of [[freedom of speech]], [[Secularism in Pakistan|secularism]] and [[Education in Pakistan|education]] in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1546317/corona-our-debt-to-darwin|title=Corona \u2014 our debt to Darwin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/national/14-Apr-2003/muslims-must-stop-glorifying-terrorism-hoodbhoy| title = Muslims must stop glorifying terrorism: Hoodbhoy| website = DailyTimes| access-date = 2016-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://thediplomat.com/2015/11/interview-pervez-hoodbhoy/| title = Interview: Pervez Hoodbhoy| last = Diplomat| first = Muhammad Akbar Notezai, The| website = The Diplomat| access-date = 2016-02-27}}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[Karachi]], Hoodbhoy studied at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] for nine years, where he received degrees in electrical engineering, mathematics and [[solid-state physics]], eventually leading to a [[PhDs|PhD]] in [[nuclear physics]]. In 1981, Hoodbhoy went on to conduct [[Postdoctoral researcher|post-doctoral]] research at the [[University of Washington]], before leaving to serve as a [[Visiting scholar|visiting professor]] at the [[Carnegie Mellon University]] in 1985. While still a professor at the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]], Hoodbhoy worked as a guest scientist at the [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics]] between 1986 until 1994. He remained with the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]] until 2010, throughout which he held visiting professorships at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] and [[Stanford Linear Collider]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eacpe.org/content/uploads/2014/02/PH-CV-2013.pdf|title=Curriculum vitae for Pervez Amirali Hoodbhoy|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Hoodbhoy joined [[Lahore University of Management Sciences|LUMS]] while simultaneously working as a researcher with the [[Princeton University]] and a columnist with the ''[[Express Tribune]]''. His contract with LUMS was terminated in 2013 which resulted in a controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/458332/the-pervez-hoodbhoy-lums-dispute/|title=The Pervez Hoodbhoy-LUMS dispute \u2013 The Express Tribune|date=2012-10-30|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref> He is a sponsor of the ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'', and a member of the monitoring panel on terrorism of the World Federation of Scientists.<ref>{{Cite web|title = PMP \u2013 Terrorism|url = http://www.federationofscientists.org/pmpanels/terrorism/Terrorism.asp|website = www.federationofscientists.org|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> Hoodbhoy has won several awards including the [[Abdus Salam]] [[Abdus Salam Award|Prize]] for Mathematics (1984);<ref>{{Cite web|title = About Pervez Hoodbhoy|url = http://eacpe.org/about-pervez-hoodbhoy/|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> the [[Kalinga Prize]] for the popularization of science (2003);<ref>{{Cite web|title = Kalinga award for Dr Hoodbhoy|url = http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/national/31-Oct-2003/kalinga-award-for-dr-hoodbhoy|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> the [[Burton Awards for Legal Achievement|Burton Award]] (2010)<ref>{{Cite web|title = Prize Recipient|url = http://www.aps.org/programs/honors/prizes/prizerecipient.cfm?last_nm=Hoodbhoy&first_nm=Pervez&year=2010|website = www.aps.org|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> from the [[American Physical Society]]. In 2011, he was included in the list of 100 most influential global thinkers by ''[[Foreign Policy]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The FP Top 100 Global Thinkers|url = https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/11/28/the-fp-top-100-global-thinkers-3/|website = Foreign Policy|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, he was made a member of the UN Secretary General's Advisory Board on Disarmament.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Secretary-General Appoints Replacements for Outgoing Members of Advisory Board on Disarmament Matters {{!}} Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|url = https://www.un.org/press/en/2012/dc3407.doc.htm|website = www.un.org|accessdate = 27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHoodbhoy remains one of Pakistan's most prominent academics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1234746|title=Back from the enemy country|first=Pervez|last=Hoodbhoy|date=23 January 2016|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref> He is the author of ''Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality''<ref>{{Cite book|title = Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality|url = https://books.google.com/?id=RKSyQgAACAAJ|publisher = Zed Books|date = 1 January 1991|isbn = 9781856490245|first = Pervez|last = Hoodbhoy}}</ref> He is the head of [[Mashal (organisation)|''Mashal'']] Books in Lahore, which claims to make \"a major translation effort to produce books in Urdu that promote modern thought, human rights, and emancipation of women\". Hoodbhoy has written for ''[[Project Syndicate]]'', [[DAWN (newspaper)|''DAWN'']],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1402940|title=What India owes to Nehru|first=Pervez|last=Hoodbhoy|date=21 April 2018|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1496468|title=Pakistan\u2019s slice of the moon|first=Pervez|last=Hoodbhoy|date=27 July 2019|website=DAWN.COM}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Express Tribune]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Pervez Hoodbhoy \u2013 Project Syndicate|url = http://www.project-syndicate.org/columnist/pervez-hoodbhoy|website = www.project-syndicate.org|access-date = 2016-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Pakistan, the Saudis' Indispensable Nuclear Partner|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/22/opinion/toward-a-saudi-pakistani-rift.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2015-04-21|access-date = 2016-02-17|issn = 0362-4331|first = Pervez|last = Hoodbhoy}}</ref> Hoodbhoy is generally considered one of the most vocal, progressive and liberal member of the Pakistani [[intelligentsia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/19373/calling-dr-pervez-hoodbhoy-jahil-can-only-happen-in-pakistan/|title=Calling Dr Pervez Hoodbhoy 'jahil' can only happen in Pakistan|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref> His daughter, [[Alia Amirali]], is also a well-known feminist and political activist.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn and raised in [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], Hoodbhoy passed the competitive [[O-Level]] and [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]] exams after attending the famed [[Karachi Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716211940/http://old.drsohail.com/Articals/Pervezhoodbhoy.htm |archivedate=16 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> After earning a scholarship, Hoodbhoy went to the United States to attend the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT).<ref name=\"Geo News\">{{cite episode| title =A Day with Geo: Interview with Pervez Hoodbhoy| episodelink =| url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MmzoYZjFEJE| series =| serieslink =| credits =| network =Geo News| station =| location =Islamabad| airdate =28 April 2011| began =| ended =| season =| seriesno =| number =| minutes =30:00| transcript =| transcripturl= }}</ref> While attending the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] in [[Massachusetts]], Hoodbhoy worked for a local [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistani restaurant]] based in [[Massachusetts]] to support his studies and showed a great interest in [[Electronic engineering|electronics]] and mathematics.<ref>http://www.newslinemagazine.com/2012/08/interview-dr-pervez-hoodbhoy/</ref>\n\nAt [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], Hoodbhoy graduated with [[double major|double]] BSc in [[Electrical Engineering]] and mathematics in 1971, followed by MS in [[physics]] with a concentration in [[solid-state physics]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Global Zero\">{{Cite web|title =Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy | work =Global Zero | publisher=Global Zero | url =http://www.globalzero.org/en/who/pervez-hoodbhoy | doi = | accessdate =January 1, 2011}}</ref> After graduation, Hoodbhoy joined the [[Quaid-e-Azam University]] (QAU) as a researcher and renewed his scholarship to resume his studies in the United States.<ref name=\"Geo TV\" />\n\nHoodbhoy continued his research in doctoral studies in [[physics]] at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], and was awarded PhD in [[nuclear physics]] in 1978.<ref name=\"Geo TV\"/> In the United States, his collaboration took place with the [[:Category:Manhattan Project people|scientists]] who participated in well known [[Manhattan Project]] in the 1940s, who subsequently influenced in his philosophy.<ref name=\"Geo TV\">{{Cite video\n | people =Parvez Hood Bhoy\n | title =ADGKS Parvez Hood Bhoy 187605 C1.mp4\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgENuWF7blM&feature=channel\n | medium =Television Production\n | publisher =Geo TV\n | location =\n | date =2010 }}\n</ref> Hoodbhoy remained a post-doctoral research fellow at the [[University of Washington]], for a short time.<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/> In 1973, Hoodbhoy joined the [[Pakistan Institute of Physics|Institute of Physics]] of the [[University of Engineering and Technology, Lahore|University of Engineering and Technology]] in [[Lahore]].<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Academia ===\nHoodbhoy focused his research career extensively on [[quantum field theory]], [[Phenomenology (particle physics)|particle phenomenology]], and [[supersymmetry]] in the area of [[particle physics]].<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/> After receiving PhD from [[MIT]], Hoodbhoy met [[Riazuddin (physicist)|Riazuddin]] and [[Abdus Salam]]\u2013 the prominent Pakistani physicists who were visiting the [[MIT]] to give lectures on particle physics. Subsequently, he joined the group of Pakistani physicists at the [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics]] in [[Trieste, Italy|Trieste]], Italy.<ref name=\"Hoodbhoy\"/> At [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics|ICTP]], Hoodbhoy collaborated with Pakistan's leading theoretical physicists who worked under [[Abdus Salam]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"Hoodbhoy\">{{Cite web | last =Hoodbhoy | first =Pervez | title =Fascinating encounters: Prof Abdus Salam | publisher =Hoodbhoy | url =http://www.globalwebpost.com/farooqm/study_res/abdus_salam/encounter.html | accessdate =January 1, 2011 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150924022536/http://www.globalwebpost.com/farooqm/study_res/abdus_salam/encounter.html | archivedate =24 September 2015 | df =dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics|ICTP]] work, Hoodbhoy returned to Pakistan to join [[Quaid-e-Azam University]] (QAU) where he began teaching and lecturing on physics. Eventually, he became chairman of [[Institute of Theoretical Physics, Qau|Institute of Theoretical Physics]] (now department of physics). After spending more than 30 years at [[Quaid-e-Azam University|Qau]], Hoodbhoy moved to [[Lahore]] where he joined the [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]] as a visiting professor, while remains a visiting scientist at the [[Stanford Linear Accelerator Center]].<ref name=\"Global Zero\"/> Controversy over his contract in [[Lahore University of Management Sciences|LUMS]] sparked an academic debate when it was reported in the [[Pakistani media|news media]] that Hoodbhoy's email to [[Vice-Chancellor]] of [[Lahore University of Management Sciences|LUMS]] was made public.<ref name=\"Express Tribune, 2012\">{{cite news|last1=Shaukat|first1=Aroosa|title=LUMS vs Hoodbhoy: I'm losing job for 'ideological reasons', says professor|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/456391/lums-vs-hoodbhoy-im-losing-job-for-ideological-reasons-says-professor/|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Express Tribune|publisher=Express Tribune, 2012|date=25 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Express Tribune\">{{cite news|last1=Haider|first1=Ejaz|title=The Pervez Hoodbhoy-LUMS dispute|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/458332/the-pervez-hoodbhoy-lums-dispute/|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Express Tribune|newspaper=Express Tribune|date=30 October 2012}}</ref> Eventually, Hoodbhoy moved to [[Forman Christian College University]] permanently and joined the senior staff to instructed courses on physics.<ref name=\"Forman College University Press\" />\n\nPrior to his return to Pakistan in 1976, the secretive development program on [[Pakistan and its Nuclear Deterrent Program|nuclear deterrence]] was near completion and Hoodbhoy was aware of the program.<ref name=\"Newsweek, 2013\">{{cite news|last1=Hoodbhoy|first1=Pervez|title=The Man Who Designed Pakistan's Bomb|url=http://newsweekpakistan.com/|accessdate=13 February 2015|work=Special biographical article in the honor of Dr. Riazuddin|agency=Newsweek|publisher=Newsweek, 2013|date=30 November 2013|archiveurl=http://newsweekpakistan.com/the-man-who-designed-pakistans-bomb/.|archivedate=30 November 2013|location=Islamabad, Pakistan|pages=5}}</ref> Hoodbhoy maintains his close ties with Pakistan's vibrant [[Pakistan Nuclear Society|nuclear society]], and had collaborated with many of country's leading theoretical physicists throughout his career, mainly with [[Ishfaq Ahmad]].<ref name=\"Newsweek, 2013\"/> On several occasions, Hoodbhoy staunchly countered Dr. [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]]'s \"father-of\" claims, and roundly criticized his academic research on [[nuclear physics]].<ref name=\"Stanford University Press\">{{cite book|last1=Khan|first1=Feroz Hassan|title=Eating grass : the making of the Pakistani bomb|date=2012|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, Calif.|isbn=978-0804776004}}</ref> In the 1980s, he famously debated with [[Sultan Bashiruddin Mahmood|Bashiruddin Mahmood]] on the topics of [[sunspots]], [[Life After Death|life-after-death]], and philosophy.<ref name=\"Free Press.\">Bergen, Peter L. (2011). \"\u00a7Quixotic Quest\". The longest war : the enduring conflict between America and al-Qaeda (1st Free Press trade paperback edition) New York: Free Press. {{ISBN|0743278941}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Hoodbhoy with [[Ishfaq Ahmad]] and Riazuddin, played a major and influential role in the establishment of [[National Center for Physics]] (NCP), becoming one of the earliest academic scientists who joined the NCP at its inception.\n\nHoodbhoy has roundly criticized the development on [[nuclear weapons]], especially its [[Nuclear race|extension]] to South Asia, mainly by [[India and Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\">{{Cite web\n |last=Hoodbhoy, PhD (Nuclear Physics) \n |first=Pervez Amerali \n |title=Pakistan's nuclear bayonet \n |work=Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy, Doctor of Philosophy (Nuclear Physics), Professor of Nuclear and High-Energy Physics at the Quaid-e-Azam University and Senior academic research scientist at the [[National Center for Physics|National Center for Nuclear Physics]] \n |publisher=Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']] \n |date=23 January 2011 \n |url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/02/16/herald-exclusive-pakistans-nuclear-bayonet.html \n |accessdate=9 September 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218212415/http://www.dawn.com/2011/02/16/herald-exclusive-pakistans-nuclear-bayonet.html \n |archivedate=18 February 2011 \n}}</ref> In 2011, Hoodbhoy held India responsible for Pakistan's symmetric [[Pakistan and Nuclear Weapons|nuclear weapons programme]] as part of Pakistan's [[Minimum Credible Deterrence|self-credible deterrence]].<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\" /> According to Hoodbhoy, India's [[Pokhran-I|nuclear tests]] forced Pakistan to jump into the [[Nuclear club|nuclear arena]] in 1974, and again in 1998, after war-threatening statements were made by [[Indian government]] to Pakistan; Pakistan [[Chagai-I|equalised]] this magnitude over the nuclear edge that same month.<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\"/> While believing that Pakistan's [[Pakistan and its Nuclear Deterrent Program|nuclear deterrence]] has protected the country from any [[Foreign interventionism|foreign aggression]] and preventing from numerous [[India Pakistan Wars|war threatening situations]] with India, Hoodbhoy on the other hand has raised concerns about the [[Nuclear safety and security|security]] of [[Pakistan's nuclear weapons|nuclear arsenals]] on the possibility of [[Islamic extremism|radicals]] gaining control.<ref name=\"Dr. Prof. Pervez Amerali Hoodbhoy and [[The Herald (Pakistan)|''The Herald'']]\" />\n\n=== Activism ===\nHoodbhoy is a prominent sponsor of the ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'', representing the Pakistan's delegation.<ref>CGPACS (2006) [http://www.socsci.uci.edu/events/060512_hoodbhoy/hoodbhoy6.htm 15th Annual Margolis Lecture with Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy]. The Center for Global Peace and Conflict Studies. [[University of California, Irvine]]. 12 May. Retrieved on 22 May 2008</ref>\n\nApart from his specialist field of research, Hoodbhoy extensively writes and speaks on topics ranging from [[Islamic sciences|science]] in [[Islam]] to [[Education in Pakistan|education]] and [[nuclear disarmament|arms disarmament]] issues around the world.<ref>Hoodbhoy (1998) [http://www.cs.ucsb.edu/~acha/politics/hoodbhoy.html Talk by Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy on nuclear tests in the Indian subcontinent]. The Alliance, Pakistan Students Society at MIT, and the MIT Program in Science, Technology, and Society. 12 May. Retrieved on 22 May 2008</ref> He is author of ''Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality'', that has been translated into five languages.<ref name=\"Fulbright Program\">{{Cite web   |last = (FPS)|first = Fulbright Scholar Program|authorlink = Fulbright Program|title = U.S. and Non U.S. Scholar: Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy|work = Global Zero|publisher = Fulbright Program|year = 2007|url = http://www.cies.org/NCS/2007_2008/scholars/ncs_phoodbhoy.htm|doi = |accessdate = January 1, 2011}}</ref> In this book, Hoodbhoy outlines the [[History of Pakistan|history]] of Pakistan, implications of [[theocracy]] and [[Martial law in Pakistan|martial law]] in Pakistan, and the [[Pakistani textbooks controversy|textbook revival]] in education system of Pakistan. His articles on various issues related to science and [[social issues]] are often published in international media. His publications are repeatedly published in both technical and non-technical papers.\n{{Quote box\n |title = \n |quote = Though I know that it is not welcome in my country and people who deviate from the notion that it is an Islamic state, are looked upon disapprovingly, I strongly feel that's what we need to head towards.\n |source = [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Pak-was-born-in-a-state-of-confusion-Hoodbhoy/articleshow/50516062.cms Talking to the Hyderabad Literary Festival]\n |align=right\n |width=30%\n}}\n[[File:Solidarity message to ex-Muslims - Pervez Hoodbhoy.webm|thumb|Pervez Hoodbhoy criticises Pakistani attitudes on \"[[blasphemy]]\".]]\nHoodbhoy widely writes about the role and modernisation of [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistan military]], particularly the defence budget spending by the [[Government of Pakistan|Pakistan government]] on the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|military]]. In an interview on [[secularism]], he mentioned that obsession with scientific-religious [[apophenia]] may have caused lack of scientific advancement among [[Muslim world|Muslims]] in recent years.<ref>[http://www.meforum.org/2593/pervez-amirali-hoodbhoy-islam-science Pervez Amirali Hoodbhoy: \"Islam and Science Have Parted Ways\"]; Interview in ''Middle East Quarterly''; Winter 2010, pp. 69\u201374, Retrieved 2 March 2012</ref> In 2003 he was one the signers of the [[Humanism and Its Aspirations|Humanist Manifesto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanhumanist.org/Humanism/Humanist_Manifesto_III/Notable_Signers |title=Notable Signers |publisher=American Humanist Association |work=Humanism and Its Aspirations |accessdate=6 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005105825/http://www.americanhumanist.org/Humanism/Humanist_Manifesto_III/Notable_Signers |archivedate=5 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHoodbhoy has criticized the Pakistan [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|Higher Education Commission]] (HEC) for pursuing \"a drive to achieve numbers rather than quality\".<ref name=\"Shehzad\">{{cite news|last1=Shehzad|first1=Rizwan|title=Hoodbhoy feels restructuring better than saving old HEC|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/483217/hoodbhoy-feels-restructuring-better-than-saving-old-hec/|accessdate=1 July 2015|agency=Tribune.com.pk|date=23 December 2012}}</ref> He believes that because of \"policies that reward authors of research articles and PhD supervisors with cash and promotions\", universities in Pakistan have \"turned into factories producing junk papers and PhDs.\"<ref name=\"HOODBHOY-29-11-14\">{{cite news|last1=Hoodbhoy|first1=Pervez|title=Misjudging universities|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1147559|accessdate=1 July 2015|agency=Dawn|date=29 November 2014}}</ref>\nHe has been a harsh critic on the performance of [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]] since 2003 when it was led by Dr. [[Atta ur Rahman (scientist)|Atta-ur-Rahman]], and the issue has led to heated debates in Pakistan's [[News channels in Pakistan|news media]].<ref name=\"Pakistaniaat\" />\n\nIn 2009 Hoodbhoy came into conflict with [[Atta ur Rahman (scientist)|Atta-ur-Rahman]], an [[Organic Chemistry|organic chemist]], over the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|Higher Education Commission]] (HEC). In the United States, the journal [[Nature (journal)|''Nature'']] published an article on the successes and failures of the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]].<ref name=\"Pakistaniat, 2009\">{{cite web|last1=Najam|first1=Adil|title=Pakistan in Higher Education|url=http://pakistaniat.com/2009/09/03/nature-pakistan-higher-education/|publisher=Pakistaniat, 2009|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> Hoodbhoy wrote to complain about, among other things, the article's failure to mention (what Hoodbhoy called) \"the billions wasted on mindless prestige mega-projects\".<ref name=\"Pakistaniaat\" />\nIn the debate on [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]] [[Adil Najam]], [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]], and [[Atta ur Rahman (scientist)|Atta-ur-Rehman]] defended the HEC while agreeing with some of Hoodbhoy's criticism.<ref name=\"Pakistaniaat\">{{cite news|last1=Najam |first1=Adil |title=Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy Responds to Nature Article on Pakistan's Higher Education Reform |url=http://pakistaniat.com/2009/09/05/hoodbhoy-nature-pakistan-education-reform/ |accessdate=13 February 2015 |agency=Pakistaniaat |publisher=Pakistaniaat |date=9 September 2009 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626160300/http://pakistaniat.com/2009/09/05/hoodbhoy-nature-pakistan-education-reform/ |archivedate=26 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAdministrative competency of [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]] was called into question by Hoodbhoy who describe the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]]'s achievement \"dismal\".<ref name=\"Dawn newspapers, 2012\">{{cite news|last1=Hassan|first1=Shazia|title=HEC lost track by focusing on quantity rather than quality'|url=http://dawn.com/news/773021/hec-lost-track-by-focusing-on-quantity-rather-than-quality|accessdate=13 February 2015|agency=Dawn newspapers, 2012|publisher=Dawn newspapers, 2012|date=12 December 2012}}</ref> Hoodbhoy supported his arguments against [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]]'s productivity, that in the case of [[Lille University of Science and Technology|UESTP-France]] convention in [[Karachi]], out of an expected faculty strength of between 450 and 600, no French faculty or administrative staff actually arrived.<ref name=\"Dawn newspapers, 2012\" /> At the television debate, Hoodbhoy questioned the statistics used to support the positive appraisal of HEC's activities in a series of communications between Hoodbhoy and HEC chairman Atta-Ur-Rehman.<ref>{{cite web|title=HEC's performance by Atta ur Rehman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TYiNGvfbM-A|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoodbhoy|title=The HEC {{sic|nolink=y|Controvery}}- Separating Fact and fiction|url=https://vimeo.com/61231182|website=Vimeo}}</ref> It was claimed by the latter that in mathematics, Pakistani authors received 20% more citations than the worldwide average. Hoodbhoy questioned this on several grounds including the number of self-citations these publications received and said that this was a crucial aspect that the HEC left out of its interpretation. Criticism was leveled by Hoodbhoy at the practice of hiring those foreign academics in local universities who were said to have difficulty in communicating and teaching, although they contributed to boosting the number of research publications originating from Pakistani universities.\n\n=== Research ===\nHoodbhoy has made important contributions in physics, particularly in particle physics. Many of Hoodbhoy's recorded lectures on physics are available online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://urduphysicslectures.blogspot.com/|title=General Physics Lectures In English}}</ref> At [[National Center for Physics]], Hoodbhoy conducted research on different aspects of particle physics, and pioneered studies in modern physics and its extension to mathematical and nuclear physics. In 2006, Hoodbhoy published a brief mathematical description of [[Generalized Parton Distributions]]. In 2007, Hoodbhoy re-published the work of Jens Lyng Peterson the [[AdS/CFT correspondence|Maldacena conjecture]] (a conjectured equivalence between a string theory and gravity defined on one space, and a quantum field theory without gravity defined by one or less dimension) where he contributed mathematically to the theory.<ref>{{Cite conference | first =Jens Lyng | last =Peterson | authorlink = |author2=Dr. Prof. Pervez Hoodbhoy | title=Introduction to Maldacena conjecture | pages=41| publisher =Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy of National Center for Physics; Second National Winter Meeting on Particles and Fields and Jens Lyng Peterson | date = 28\u201331 December 2009 | location =Islamabad, Islamabad Capital Territory | url=http://www.ncp.edu.pk/docs/snwm/Pervez_hoodbhoy_003_Intro_to_Maldacena_Conjecture.pdf | doi = | accessdate =January 1, 2011 }}</ref> In the same year, he re-published the work of [[Edward Witten]] on [[Anti-de Sitter space]] and its extension to the field of [[Holography]]. While the paper was published experimentally in 1998 by Witten, Hoodbhoy provided the brief mathematical proofs and description to understand, logically, the subject of Sitter space\u2014 a [[scalar curvature]] in general theory of relativity.<ref>{{Cite conference | first=Dr. Prof. Edward | last=Witten | authorlink =Edward Witten |author2=Dr. Prof. Pervez Hoodbhoy | title =Anti de Sitter Space and Holography|pages =41| publisher=Dr. Pervez Hoodbhoy of National Center for Physics; Second National Winter Meeting on Particles and Fields and Edward Witten (1998)| date = 28\u201331 December 2009 | location =Islamabad, Islamabad Capital Territory |url=http://www.ncp.edu.pk/docs/snwm/Pervez_hoodbhoy_004_Holography_Witten.pdf | doi = | accessdate=January 1, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April 2001, it was announced that Dr. Hoodbhoy would be receiving [[Sitara-e-Imtiaz|''Sitara-i-Imtiaz'']] from the former [[President of Pakistan|President]], General (retired) [[Pervez Musharraf]] which he refused to accept. His refusal prompted the [[The Friday Times|''Friday Times'']] to interview him.\n\n{{quote|text=I am reasonably [satisfied] with my (scientific) work... I do not think it is earth-shaking or... that it deserves any kind of [award]. On the other hand, receiving an [award] \u2013 even if it is a high national award \u2013 would give me absolutely no sense of achievement or satisfaction... because it carries no credibility or prestige in professional circles. Such things do not indicate that you have done good work in your field. Therefore I decided to refuse the award.|sign=Pervez Hoodbhoy, <small>issued the statement on ''The Friday Times'', 2001</small>|source=<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hoodbhoy|first=Pervez|date=23 April 2001|url=http://www.chowk.com/articles/5034|title=Refusing The Sitara-I-Imtiaz|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121155705/http://chowk.com/articles/5034}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Filmography ===\nHe produced a 13-part documentary series in [[Urdu]] for [[Pakistan Television]] on critical issues in education, and two series aimed at popularising science. In 2004, he made a documentary film '[[Crossing the Lines]]: Kashmir, Pakistan, India' along with Dr. [[Zia Mian]].<ref>CGPACS (2006) [http://www.socsci.uci.edu/files/socsci/announcements/060512_hoodbhoy/crossingthelines.htm Crossing the Lines: Kashmir, Pakistan, India]</ref> These documentaries carry heavy emphasis on the issues of education, public health and scientific revolution in Pakistan.\n\nIn his documentaries, Dr. Hoodbhoy has heavily criticised Pakistan and India's nuclear weapons program. He also pointed out the seriousness of the Talibanization in Pakistan and its immediate effects on South Asia. His documentaries also point out that American and [[NATO]] forces in Afghanistan didn't help the Afghan people's life and there was no reform in Afghanistan's social and public sector and, instead, the insurgency and corruption grew, which also destabilised Pakistan's western front.<ref name=\"Fulbright Program\"/>\n* ''Crossing the Lines: Kashmir, Pakistan, India'' (2004)\n* ''The Bell Tolls for Planet Earth'' (2003)\n* ''Pakistan and India Under the Nuclear Shadow'' (2001)\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Education and the State: Fifty Years Of Pakistan'' [[Oxford University Press]], 1998. {{ISBN|978-0-19-577825-0}}\n* ''Islam and Science: Religious Orthodoxy and the Battle for Rationality'' Zed Books, London, 1992. {{ISBN|978-1-85649-025-2}}, (Translations in [[Arabic]], [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], [[Malay language|Malaysian]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], Japanese, and [[Urdu]])\n* (Co-Edited with A. Ali), ''Proceedings of the School on Fundamental Physics and Cosmology'' World Scientific, Singapore, 1991.\n* (With [[A H Nayyar|A. H. Nayyar]]), \"Rewriting the History of Pakistan\", in ''Islam, Politics and the State: The Pakistan Experience'', Ed. Mohammad Asghar Khan, Zed Books, London, 1986. {{ISBN|978-0-86232-471-1}}\n\n===Scientific papers and articles===\n* Two-Photon Effects in Lepton-AntiLepton Pair Photoproduction from a Nucleon Target using Real Photons, Authors: Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 73 (2006) 054027\n* Probing Quark Distribution Amplitudes Through Generalized Parton Distributions at Large Momentum Transfer, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Feng Yuan, Phys. Rev. Lett. 92 (2004) 012003\n* Explicit Proof that Electroproduction of Transversely Polarized Vector Mesons Vanishes in Perturbative QCD, Pervez Hoodbhoy (University of Maryland and Quaid-e-Azam University), Phys. Rev. D 65 (2002) 077501\n* Does the Gluon Spin Contribute in A Gauge Invariant Way to Nucleon Spin? Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Phys. Rev. D 60 (1999) 114042\n* Nucleon-Quarkonium Elastic Scattering and the Gluon Contribution to Nucleon Spin, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. Lett. 82 (1999) 4985\u20134987\n* Implications of Color Gauge Symmetry For Nucleon Spin Structure, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Wei Lu, Phys. Rev. D 59 (1999) 074010\n* Quark Orbital-Angular-Momentum Distribution in the Nucleon, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Wei Lu, Phys. Rev. D 59 (1999) 014013\n* Helicity-Flip Off-Forward Parton Distributions of the Nucleon, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Ji, Phys. Rev. D 58 (1998) 054006\n* Wavefunction corrections and off-forward gluon distributions in diffractive J/psi electroproduction, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 56 (1997) 388\u2013393\n* Relativistic and Binding Energy Corrections to Direct Photon Production In Upsilon Decay, Mohammad Ali Yusuf, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 54 (1996) 3345\u20133349\n* Beyond The Colour-Singlet Model For Inelastic J_psi Photoproduction, H. Khan, P. Hoodbhoy, Phys. Lett. B382 (1996) 189\n* The Spin Structure of the Nucleon in the Asymptotic Limit, X. Ji, J. Tang (MIT), P. Hoodbhoy (Quaid-e-Azam, Pakistan), Phys. Rev. Lett. 76 (1996) 740\u2013743\n* Novel approach to decays, gluon distributions, and fragmentation functions of heavy quarkonia, Rafia Ali, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 51 (1995) 2302\u20132310\n* Quark fragmentation functions in a diquark model for proton and $\\Lambda$ hyperon production, Muhammad Nzar, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 51 (1995) 32\u201336\n* Systematic gauge invariant approach to heavy quarkonium decays, Hafsa Khan, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Phys. Rev. D 53 (1996) 2534\u20132540\n* Twist-Four Distributions in a Transversely-Polarized Nucleon and the Drell-Yan Process, Pevrez Hoodbhoy, Xiangdong Xi, Phys. Rev. D 50 (1994) 4429\u20134435\n* Detecting Two-Photon Exchange Effects in Hard Scattering from Nucleon Targets, in [[Mathematical Physics]]: Proceedings of the 12th Regional Conference, Islamabad, Pakistan 27 March \u2013 1 April 2006, World Scientific, Singapore, 2007. {{ISBN|978-981-270-591-4}}\n* Abdus Salam: Past and Present- The News (29 January 1996)\n* [http://www.ncp.edu.pk/docs/12th_rgdocs/Pervez-Hoodbhoy.pdf Generalized Parton Distributions], Pervez Hoodbhoy, Quaid-e-Azam University, Islamabad\n\n==Appearances in TV shows==\n* ''Raaste Ilm ke'' (Pathways to Knowledge) on [[PTV Home|PTV]], 1988\n* ''Asrar-e-Jahan'' (Mysteries of the Universe) on [[PTV Home|PTV]], 1995\n* ''Bazm-e-Kainat'' (Gathering of all Creation)  on [[PTV Home|PTV]], 2003\n* ''Alif'' on Geo TV. Debate with Jawed Ghamidi, 2006\n* ''Aik Din Geo Kay Saath'' on [[Geo TV]], February 2010\n* ''Capital Talk'' on [[Geo TV]], 29 August 2012\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{in lang|de}} Kaznain, Hazim. \"[http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/interview-mit-dem-pakistanischen-atomphysiker-pervez-hoodbhoy-a-879319.html Pakistanischer Atomphysiker: \"Muslimische Gesellschaften sind kollektiv gescheitert]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6XSb5PCI6?url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/interview-mit-dem-pakistanischen-atomphysiker-pervez-hoodbhoy-a-879319.html Archive]). ''[[Der Spiegel]]''. Monday 28 January 2013. Interview with Hoodbhoy.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.simloo.com A complete repository of Pervez Hoodbhoy's articles in the making]\n* [http://www.qau.edu.pk/profile.php?id=yLn9T Profile], QAU\n* [http://www.zmag.org/zspace/search/znetarticles/pervezhoodbhoy Pervez Hoodbhoy's recent articles for Z Magazine]\n* [http://www.chowk.com/show_writer_page.cgi?pen_name=Pervez%20Hoodbhoy Pervez Hoodbhoy's articles for the website Chowk.com]\n* [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Pervez+Hoodbhoy&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en&btnG=Search Pervez Hoodbhoy's research papers]\n* [http://ptonline.aip.org/journals/doc/PHTOAD-ft/vol_60/iss_8/49_1.shtml Science and the Islamic world\u2014The quest for rapprochement], Pervez Hoodbhoy, [[American Institute of Physics]], August 2007\n* [http://cgs.illinois.edu/resources/webvideo/sacred-terror-theirs-and-ours Video Presentation:] \"Sacred Terror: Theirs and Ours.\" Professor Hoodbhoy speaking at the University of Illinois, October 2007.\n* [http://www.himalmag.com/Pakistan-s-westward-drift_nw1947.html Pakistan's westward drift] \u2013 article by P Hoodbhoy lamenting the rising tide of [[militant Islam]] in Pakistan\n* [http://www.prospect-magazine.co.uk/article_details.php?id=4244 Islamic Failure] \u2013 2002 article by P Hoodbhoy, first published in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and reprinted in ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoodbhoy, Pervez Amirali}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Pakistani physicists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Ismailis]]\n[[Category:Pakistani democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani educators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani scientists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani scholars]]\n[[Category:Pakistani science writers]]\n[[Category:Kalinga Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lahore University of Management Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani anti\u2013nuclear weapons activists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:Quaid-i-Azam University faculty]]\n[[Category:Pakistani anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:Karachi Grammar School alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani humanists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani science journalists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani secularists]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pakistan Philosophical Congress]]\n[[Category:MIT Department of Physics alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Mashal (organisation)closed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pervez_Hoodbhoy"}
{"title_page": "Uncle Sargam", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour        = silver\n| name          = Uncle Sargam\n| series        = Kaliyan, Sargam Time, Daak Time, Siyasi Kaliyan, Sargam Back Home\n| image         = FAROOQ QAISAR.jpg\n| image_size    = 220px\n| caption       = [[Farooq Qaiser]] and his puppet Uncle Sargam\n| first         = 1976\n| creator       = [[Farooq Qaiser]]\n| portrayer     = \n| voice         = Farooq Qaiser\n| lbl1          = \n| data1         = \n| lbl2          = \n| data2         = \n| lbl3          = \n| data3         = \n| info-hdr      =\n| noinfo        =\n| full_name      =\n| nickname      = Sargam\n| alias         = \n| gender        = Male\n| occupation    = \n| title         = \n| family        = \n| spouse        = \n| significant_other = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| religion      = [[Muslim]]\n| nationality   = [[Pakistan]]i\n| lbl21         = \n| data21        = \n| lbl22         = \n| data22        = \n| lbl23         = \n| data23        = \n| extra-hdr     = \n| lbl31         = \n| data31        = \n| lbl32         = \n| data32        = \n| lbl33         = \n| data33        =\n}}\n\n'''Uncle Sargam''' ({{lang-ur|\u0627\u0646\u06a9\u0644 \u0633\u0631\u06af\u0645}}) is a [[puppet]] character that first appeared in the Pakistani children's television show ''Kaliyan'', aired on [[PTV Home|PTV]] in 1976.<ref name=decades>{{cite news|title=Paying tribute: After decades, Uncle Sargam remains darling of the crowd|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/394859/paying-tribute-after-decades-uncle-sargam-remains-darling-of-the-crowd/|accessdate=26 March 2013|newspaper=[[tribune.com.pk]]|date=17 June 2012}}</ref> Uncle Sargam was created and voiced by the award-winning puppeteer and television director [[Farooq Qaiser]].<ref name=\"decades\" /> Uncle Sargam and Maasi Museebtay are regarded as Pakistan's legendary puppet duo.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Subba|first1=Bhim|title=Kidstuff: A Resource Book for Media Covering Children in South and South East Asia|date=2000|publisher=Panos Institute South Asia|isbn=9789993330462|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T1XaAAAAMAAJ&q=uncle+sargam&dq=uncle+sargam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj83-qnmZjZAhWMKewKHWH3BFcQ6AEINTAD|accessdate=9 February 2018|quote=First, they called on the services of Uncle Sargam and Maasi Museebte, Pakistan's legendary puppet duo, to put on a command performance for the children of Thatta.}}</ref>\n\nThe satirical Uncle Sargam was the most vocal critic on [[Pakistan Television Corporation|state television]] under General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]]'s dictatorship in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Awan|first1=Nishat|title=Diasporic Agencies: Mapping the City Otherwise|date=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9781317151272|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KjklDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> Later appearances were in the TV show ''Daak Time'' in 1993. The character appeared and hosted a television talk show ''Syasi Kaliyan'' at [[Dawn News]] in 2010.\n\nThe character also appeared in a [[Pakistan National Council of the Arts]]-organised show in [[Islamabad]].<ref name=\"decades\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Uncle Sargam\u2019 revives old memories|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C06%5C16%5Cstory_16-6-2012_pg11_12|accessdate=26 March 2013|newspaper=[[dailytimes.com.pk]]|date=16 June 2012}}</ref> Uncle Sargam later appeared in a charity show function organised by the NGO Mashal at the [[National Library of Pakistan]] in Islamabad in July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mashal school: Uncle Sargam lifts spirits at charity show|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/573753/mashal-school-uncle-sargam-lifts-spirits-at-charity-show/|accessdate=15 August 2013|newspaper=tribune.com.pk|date=7 July 2013}}</ref> In March 2014, the [[Oxford University Press]] held an Uncle Sargam puppet show to help children differentiate between original and pirated books at [[Peshawar]]\u2019s Archives Library.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farooq|first1=Umer|title=First edition: Children learn about piracy from Uncle Sargam|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/687683/first-edition-children-learn-about-piracy-from-uncle-sargam/|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=Express Tribune|date=March 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a [[diorama]] of Uncle Sargam was inaugurated at [[Lok Virsa Museum]] in [[Islamabad]] as a tribute to both the character and Farooq Qaiser.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kundi|first1=Asma|title=Lok Virsa pays tribute to Uncle Sargam creator Farooq Qaiser|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1179431/lok-virsa-pays-tribute-to-uncle-sargam-creator-farooq-qaiser|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=Dawn|date=9 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jabri|first1=Parvez|title=Uncle Sargam Diorama inaugurated at Heritage Museum|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2018/02/09/398042/uncle-sargam-diorama-inaugurated-at-heritage-museum/|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=Business Recorder|date=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite news|last1=Ali|first1=Muhammad|title=Recalling Uncle Sargam through Omar Gilani\u2019s painting|url=https://nation.com.pk/15-Dec-2016/recalling-uncle-sargram-through-omar-gilani-s-painting|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=The Nation|date=December 15, 2016}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{facebook|UncleSargam}}\n\n[[Category:Puppets]]\n[[Category:Fictional puppets]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1976]]\n[[Category:Fictional Pakistani people]]\n\n\n{{Puppet-stub}}\n{{tv-char-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour        = silver\n| name          = Uncle Sargam\n| series        = Kaliyan, Sargam Time, Daak Time, Siyasi Kaliyan, Sargam Back Home\n| image         = FAROOQ QAISAR.jpg\n| image_size    = 220px\n| caption       = [[Farooq Qaiser]] and his puppet Uncle Sargam\n| first         = 1976\n| creator       = [[Farooq Qaiser]]\n| portrayer     = \n| voice         = Farooq Qaiser\n| lbl1          = \n| data1         = \n| lbl2          = \n| data2         = \n| lbl3          = \n| data3         = \n| info-hdr      =\n| noinfo        =\n| full_name      =\n| nickname      = Sargam\n| alias         = \n| gender        = Male\n| occupation    = \n| title         = \n| family        = \n| spouse        = \n| significant_other = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| religion      = [[Muslim]]\n| nationality   = [[Pakistan]]i\n| lbl21         = \n| data21        = \n| lbl22         = \n| data22        = \n| lbl23         = \n| data23        = \n| extra-hdr     = \n| lbl31         = \n| data31        = \n| lbl32         = \n| data32        = \n| lbl33         = \n| data33        =\n}}\n\n'''Uncle Sargam''' ({{lang-ur|\u0627\u0646\u06a9\u0644 \u0633\u0631\u06af\u0645}}) is a [[puppet]] character that first appeared in the Pakistani children's television show ''Kaliyan'', aired on [[PTV Home|PTV]] in 1976.<ref name=decades>{{cite news|title=Paying tribute: After decades, Uncle Sargam remains darling of the crowd|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/394859/paying-tribute-after-decades-uncle-sargam-remains-darling-of-the-crowd/|accessdate=26 March 2013|newspaper=[[tribune.com.pk]]|date=17 June 2012}}</ref> Uncle Sargam was created and voiced by the award-winning puppeteer and television director [[Farooq Qaiser]].<ref name=\"decades\" /> Uncle Sargam and Maasi Museebtay are regarded as Pakistan's legendary puppet duo.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Subba|first1=Bhim|title=Kidstuff: A Resource Book for Media Covering Children in South and South East Asia|date=2000|publisher=Panos Institute South Asia|isbn=9789993330462|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T1XaAAAAMAAJ&q=uncle+sargam&dq=uncle+sargam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj83-qnmZjZAhWMKewKHWH3BFcQ6AEINTAD|accessdate=9 February 2018|quote=First, they called on the services of Uncle Sargam and Maasi Museebte, Pakistan's legendary puppet duo, to put on a command performance for the children of Thatta.}}</ref>\n\nThe satirical Uncle Sargam was the most vocal critic on [[Pakistan Television Corporation|state television]] under General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]]'s dictatorship in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Awan|first1=Nishat|title=Diasporic Agencies: Mapping the City Otherwise|date=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9781317151272|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KjklDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> Later appearances were in the TV show ''Daak Time'' in 1993. The character appeared and hosted a television talk show ''Syasi Kaliyan'' at [[Dawn News]] in 2010.\n\nThe character also appeared in a [[Pakistan National Council of the Arts]]-organised show in [[Islamabad]].<ref name=\"decades\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Uncle Sargam\u2019 revives old memories|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012%5C06%5C16%5Cstory_16-6-2012_pg11_12|accessdate=26 March 2013|newspaper=[[dailytimes.com.pk]]|date=16 June 2012}}</ref> Uncle Sargam later appeared in a charity show function organised by the NGO [[Mashal (organisation)|Mashal]] at the [[National Library of Pakistan]] in Islamabad in July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mashal school: Uncle Sargam lifts spirits at charity show|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/573753/mashal-school-uncle-sargam-lifts-spirits-at-charity-show/|accessdate=15 August 2013|newspaper=tribune.com.pk|date=7 July 2013}}</ref> In March 2014, the [[Oxford University Press]] held an Uncle Sargam puppet show to help children differentiate between original and pirated books at [[Peshawar]]\u2019s Archives Library.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farooq|first1=Umer|title=First edition: Children learn about piracy from Uncle Sargam|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/687683/first-edition-children-learn-about-piracy-from-uncle-sargam/|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=Express Tribune|date=March 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a [[diorama]] of Uncle Sargam was inaugurated at [[Lok Virsa Museum]] in [[Islamabad]] as a tribute to both the character and Farooq Qaiser.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kundi|first1=Asma|title=Lok Virsa pays tribute to Uncle Sargam creator Farooq Qaiser|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1179431/lok-virsa-pays-tribute-to-uncle-sargam-creator-farooq-qaiser|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=Dawn|date=9 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jabri|first1=Parvez|title=Uncle Sargam Diorama inaugurated at Heritage Museum|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2018/02/09/398042/uncle-sargam-diorama-inaugurated-at-heritage-museum/|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=Business Recorder|date=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite news|last1=Ali|first1=Muhammad|title=Recalling Uncle Sargam through Omar Gilani\u2019s painting|url=https://nation.com.pk/15-Dec-2016/recalling-uncle-sargram-through-omar-gilani-s-painting|accessdate=9 February 2018|work=The Nation|date=December 15, 2016}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{facebook|UncleSargam}}\n\n[[Category:Puppets]]\n[[Category:Fictional puppets]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1976]]\n[[Category:Fictional Pakistani people]]\n\n\n{{Puppet-stub}}\n{{tv-char-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Mashal (organisation)closed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncle_Sargam"}
